# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: whisper-asr
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech recognition applications include voice user interfaces, where the user speaks to a device, which "listens" and processes the audio.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Common voice applications include interpreting commands for calling, call routing, home automation, and aircraft control.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] These applications are called direct voice input.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Productivity applications include searching audio recordings, creating transcripts, and dictation.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech recognition can be used to analyse speaker characteristics, such as identifying native language using pronunciation assessment.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Voice recognition (speaker identification) refers to identifying the speaker, rather than speech contents.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Recognizing the speaker can simplify the task of translating speech in systems trained on a specific person's voice.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] It can also be used to authenticate the speaker as part of a security process.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Applications for speech recognition developed over many decades, with progress accelerated due to advances in deep learning and the use of big data.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] These advances are reflected in an increase in academic papers, and greater system adoption.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Key areas of growth include vocabulary size, more accurate recognition for unfamiliar speakers (speaker independence), and faster processing speed.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Raj Reddy was the first person to work on continuous speech recognition, as a graduate student at Stanford University in the late 1960s.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Previous systems required users to pause after each word.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Reddy's system issued spoken commands for playing chess.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Around this time, Soviet researchers invented the dynamic time warping (DTW) algorithm and used it to create a recognizer capable of operating on a 200-word vocabulary.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] DTW processed speech by dividing it into short frames (e.g.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] 10 ms segments) and treating each frame as a unit.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speaker independence, however, remained unsolved.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] During the late 1960s, Leonard Baum developed the mathematics of Markov chains at the Institute for Defense Analysis.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] A decade later, at CMU, Raj Reddy's students James Baker and Janet M.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Baker began using the hidden Markov model (HMM) for speech recognition.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] James Baker had learned about HMMs while at the Institute for Defense Analysis.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] HMMs enabled researchers to combine sources of knowledge, such as acoustics, language, and syntax, in a unified probabilistic model.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] By the mid-1980s, Fred Jelinek's team at IBM created a voice-activated typewriter called Tangora, which could handle a 20,000-word vocabulary.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Jelinek's statistical approach placed less emphasis on emulating human brain processes in favor of statistical modelling.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] (Jelinek's group independently discovered the application of HMMs to speech.) This was controversial among linguists since HMMs are too simplistic to account for many features of human languages.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] However, the HMM proved to be a highly useful way for modelling speech and replaced dynamic time warping as the dominant speech recognition algorithm in the 1980s.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The 1980s also saw the introduction of the n-gram language model.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] At the end of the DARPA program in 1976, the best computer available to researchers was the PDP-10 with 4 MB of RAM.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] It could take up to 100 minutes to decode 30 seconds of speech.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] By the early 1990s, the vocabulary of the typical commercial speech recognition system had exceeded the average human vocabulary.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Reddy's former student, Xuedong Huang, developed the Sphinx-II system at CMU.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Sphinx-II was the first to do speaker-independent, large vocabulary, continuous speech recognition, and it won DARPA's 1992 evaluation.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Handling continuous speech with a large vocabulary was a major milestone.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Huang later founded the speech recognition group at Microsoft in 1993.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Reddy's student Kai-Fu Lee joined Apple, where, in 1992, he helped develop the Casper speech interface prototype.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Lernout & Hauspie, a Belgium-based speech recognition company, acquired other companies, including Kurzweil Applied Intelligence in 1997 and Dragon Systems in 2000.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] L&H was an industry leader until an accounting scandal destroyed it in 2001.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] L&H speech technology was bought by ScanSoft, which became Nuance in 2005.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Apple licensed Nuance software for its digital assistant Siri.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In the 2000s, DARPA sponsored two speech recognition programs: Effective Affordable Reusable Speech-to-Text (EARS) in 2002, followed by Global Autonomous Language Exploitation (GALE) in 2005.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Four teams participated in EARS: IBM; a team led by BBN with LIMSI and the University of Pittsburgh; Cambridge University; and a team composed of ICSI, SRI, and the University of Washington.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] EARS funded the collection of the Switchboard telephone speech corpus, which contained 260 hours of recorded conversations from over 500 speakers.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The GALE program focused on Arabic and Mandarin broadcast news.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Google's first effort at speech recognition came in 2007 after recruiting Nuance researchers.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Its first product, GOOG-411, was a telephone-based directory service.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] National Security Agency has employed keyword spotting, allowing analysts to index large volumes of recorded conversations and identify speech containing "interesting" keywords.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Other government research programs focused on intelligence applications, such as DARPA's EARS program and IARPA's Babel program.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In the early 2000s, speech recognition was dominated by hidden Markov models combined with feed-forward artificial neural networks (ANN).
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Later, speech recognition was taken over by long short-term memory (LSTM), a recurrent neural network (RNN) published by Sepp Hochreiter & Jürgen Schmidhuber in 1997.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] LSTM RNNs avoid the vanishing gradient problem and can learn "Very Deep Learning" tasks that require memories of events that happened thousands of discrete time steps earlier, which is important for speech.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Around 2007, LSTMs trained with Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC) began to outperform.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In 2015, Google reported a 49 percent error‑rate reduction in its speech recognition via CTC‑trained LSTM.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Transformers, a type of neural network based solely on attention, were adopted in computer vision and language modelling, and then to speech recognition.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Deep feed-forward (non-recurrent) networks for acoustic modelling were introduced in 2009 by Geoffrey Hinton and his students at the University of Toronto, and by Li Deng and colleagues at Microsoft Research.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In contrast to the prioer incremental improvements, deep learning decreased error rates by 30%.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Both shallow and deep forms (e.g., recurrent nets) of ANNs had been explored since the 1980s.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] However, these methods never defeated non-uniform internal-handcrafting Gaussian mixture model/hidden Markov model (GMM-HMM) technology.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Difficulties analyzed in the 1990s, included gradient diminishing and weak temporal correlation structure.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] All these difficulties combined with insufficient training data and computing power.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Most speech recognition pursued generative modelling approaches until deep learning won the day.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] By early the 2010s, speech recognition was differentiated from speaker recognition, and speaker independence was considered a major breakthrough.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Until then, systems required a "training" period for each voice.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In 2017, Microsoft researchers reached the human parity milestone of transcribing conversational speech on the widely benchmarked Switchboard task.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Multiple deep learning models were used to improve accuracy.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The error rate was reported to be as low as 4 professional human transcribers working together on the same benchmark.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Both acoustic modeling and language modeling are important parts of statistically-based speech recognition algorithms.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Hidden Markov models (HMMs) are widely used in many systems.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Language modelling is also used in many other natural language processing applications, such as document classification or statistical machine translation.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech recognition systems are based on HMMs.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] These are statistical models that output a sequence of symbols or quantities.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] HMMs are used in speech recognition because a speech signal can be viewed as a piecewise stationary signal or a short-time stationary signal.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] 10 milliseconds), speech can be approximated as a stationary process.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech can be thought of as a Markov model for many stochastic purposes.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] HMMs are popular because they can be trained automatically and are simple and computationally feasible.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] An HMM outputs a sequence of *n*-dimensional real-valued vectors (where *n* is an integer such as 10), outputting one every 10 milliseconds.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The vectors consist of cepstral coefficients, obtained by a Fourier transform of a short window of speech and decorrelating the spectrum using a cosine transform, then taking the first (most significant) coefficients.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The HMM tends to have, in each state, a statistical distribution that is a mixture of diagonal covariance Gaussians, which give a likelihood for each observed vector.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Each word, or (for more general speech recognition systems), each phoneme, has a different output distribution; an HMM for a sequence of words or phonemes is made by concatenating the individual trained HMMs for the separate words and phonemes.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech recognition systems use combinations of standard techniques to improve results.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] A typical large-vocabulary system applies context dependency for the phonemes (so that phonemes with different left and right context have different realizations as HMM states).
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] It uses cepstral normalization to handle speaker and recording conditions.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] It might use vocal tract length normalization (VTLN) for male-female normalization and maximum likelihood linear regression (MLLR) for more general adaptation.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Many systems use discriminative training techniques that dispense with a purely statistical approach to HMM parameter estimation and instead optimize some classification-related measure of the training data.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Examples are maximum mutual information (MMI), minimum classification error (MCE), and minimum phone error (MPE).
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Dynamic time warping was historically used for speech recognition, but was later displaced by HMM.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Dynamic time warping measures similarity between two sequences that may vary in time or speed.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] For instance, similarities in walking patterns could be detected, even if in one video a person was walking slowly and in another was walking more quickly, or even if accelerations and decelerations came during one observation.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] DTW has been applied to video, audio, and graphics – any data that can be turned into a linear representation can be analyzed with DTW.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] This could handle speech at different speaking speeds.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In general, it allows an optimal match between two sequences (e.g., time series) with certain restrictions.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The sequences are "warped" non-linearly to match each other.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] This sequence alignment method is often used in the context of HMMs.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Neural networks became interesting in the late 1980s before beginning to dominate in the 2010s.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Neural networks have been used in many aspects of speech recognition, such as phoneme classification, phoneme classification through multi-objective evolutionary algorithms, isolated word recognition, audiovisual speech recognition, audiovisual speaker recognition, and speaker adaptation.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Neural networks make fewer explicit assumptions about feature statistical properties than HMMs.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] When used to estimate the probabilities of a speech segment, neural networks allow natural and efficient discriminative training.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] However, in spite of their effectiveness in classifying short-time units such as individual phonemes and isolated words, early neural networks were rarely successful for continuous recognition because of their limited ability to model temporal dependencies.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] One approach was to use neural networks for feature transformation, or dimensionality reduction.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] However, more recently, LSTM and related recurrent neural networks (RNNs), Time Delay Neural Networks (TDNN's), and transformers demonstrated improved performance.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Researchers are exploring deep neural networks (DNNs) and denoising autoencoders.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] A DNN is a type of artificial neural network that includes multiple hidden layers between the input and output.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Like simpler neural networks, DNNs can model complex, non-linear relationships.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] However, their deeper architecture allows them to build more sophisticated representations that combine features from earlier layers.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] This gives them a powerful ability to learn and recognize complex patterns in speech data.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] A major breakthrough in using DNNs for large vocabulary speech recognition came in 2010.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In a collaboration between industry and academia, researchers used DNNs with large output layers based on context-dependent HMM states that were created using decision trees.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] This approach significantly improved performance.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] A core idea behind deep learning is to eliminate the need for manually designed features and instead learn directly from input data.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] This was first demonstrated using deep autoencoders trained on raw spectrograms or linear filter-bank features.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] These models outperformed traditional Mel-Cepstral features, which rely on fixed transformations.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] More recently, researchers showed that waveforms can achieve excellent results in large-scale speech recognition.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Since 2014, much research has considered "end-to-end" ASR.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Traditional phonetic-based (i.e., all HMM-based model) approaches required separate components and training for pronunciation, acoustic, and language.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] End-to-end models learn from all the components at once.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] This simplifies the training and deployment processes.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] For example, an n-gram language model is required for all HMM-based systems, and a typical 2025-era n-gram language model often takes gigabytes in memory, making them impractical to deploy on mobile devices.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Consequently, ASR systems from Google and Apple (as of 2017) deploy on servers and required a network connection to operate.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The first attempt at end-to-end ASR was the Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC)-based system introduced by Alex Graves of Google DeepMind and Navdeep Jaitly of the University of Toronto in 2014.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The model consisted of RNNs and a CTC layer.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Jointly, the RNN-CTC model learns the pronunciation and acoustic model together, however, it is incapable of learning the language model due to conditional independence assumptions, similar to an HMM.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Consequently, CTC models can directly learn to map speech acoustics to English characters, but the models make many common spelling mistakes and must rely on a separate language model to finalize transcripts.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Later, Baidu expanded on the work with extremely large datasets and demonstrated some commercial success in Mandarin and English.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In 2016, the University of Oxford presented LipNet, the first end-to-end sentence-level lipreading model, using spatiotemporal convolutions coupled with an RNN-CTC architecture, surpassing human-level performance in a restricted dataset.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] A large-scale convolutional-RNN-CTC architecture was presented in 2018 by Google DeepMind, achieving 6 times better performance than human experts.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In 2019, Nvidia launched two CNN-CTC ASR models, Jasper and QuarzNet, with an overall performance word error rate (WER) of 3%.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Similar to other deep learning applications, transfer learning and domain adaptation are important strategies for reusing and extending the capabilities of deep learning models, particularly due to the small size of available corpora in many languages and/or specific domains.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In 2018, researchers at MIT Media Lab announced preliminary work on AlterEgo, a device that uses electrodes to read the neuromuscular signals users make as they subvocalize.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] They trained a convolutional neural network to translate the electrode signals into words.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Attention-based ASR models were introduced by Chan et al. of Carnegie Mellon University and Google Brain, and Bahdanau et al. of the University of Montreal in 2016.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The model named "Listen, Attend and Spell" (LAS), literally "listens" to the acoustic signal, pays "attention" to all parts of the signal and "spells" out the transcript one character at a time.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Unlike CTC-based models, attention-based models require conditional-independence assumptions and can learn all the components of a speech recognizer directly.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] This means that during deployment, no *a priori* language model is required, making it less demanding for applications with limited memory.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Attention-based models immediately outperformed CTC models (with or without an external language model) and continued improving.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Latent Sequence Decomposition (LSD) was proposed by Carnegie Mellon University, MIT, and Google Brain to directly emit sub-word units that are more natural than English characters.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The University of Oxford and Google DeepMind extended LAS to "Watch, Listen, Attend and Spell" (WLAS) to handle lip reading and surpassed human-level performance.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Voice commands may be used to initiate phone calls, select radio stations, or play music.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Voice recognition capabilities vary across car make and model.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Some models offer natural-language speech recognition, allowing the driver to use full sentences and common phrases in a conversational style.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] With such systems, fixed commands are not required.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Automatic pronunciation assessment is the use of speech recognition to verify the correctness of speech, as distinguished from assessment by a person.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Pronunciation assessment does not determine unknown speech (as in dictation or automatic transcription) but instead, compares speech to a reference model for the words spoken, sometimes with inconsequential prosody such as intonation, pitch, tempo, rhythm, and stress.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Pronunciation assessment is also used in reading tutoring, for example in products such as Microsoft Teams and Amira Learning.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Pronunciation assessment can also be used to help diagnose and treat speech disorders such as apraxia.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Assessing intelligibility is essential for avoiding inaccuracies from accent bias, especially in high-stakes assessments, from words with multiple correct pronunciations, and from phoneme coding errors in digital pronunciation dictionaries.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In 2022, researchers found that some newer speech to text systems, based on end-to-end reinforcement learning to map audio signals directly into words, produce word and phrase confidence scores closely correlated with listener intelligibility.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In the Common European Framework of Reference for Languages (CEFR) assessment criteria for "overall phonological control", intelligibility outweighs formally correct pronunciation at all levels.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In the health care sector, speech recognition can be implemented in front-end or back-end medical documentation processes.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In front-end speech recognition, the provider dictates into a speech-recognition engine, words are displayed as they are recognized, and the speaker is responsible for editing and signing off on the document.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In back-end or deferred speech recognition the provider speaks into a digital dictation system, the voice is routed through a speech-recognition machine, and a draft document is routed along with the voice file to an editor, who edits/finalizes the draft and final report.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] A major issue is that the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 (ARRA) provides substantial financial benefits to physicians who utilize an Electronic Health Record (EHR) that complies with "Meaningful Use" standards.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] These standards require that substantial data be maintained by the EHR.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] A more significant issue is that most EHRs have not been expressly tailored to take advantage of voice-recognition capabilities.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] A large part of a clinician's interaction with EHR involves navigation through the user interface that is heavily dependent on keyboard and mouse; voice-based navigation provides only modest ergonomic benefits.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Prolonged use of speech recognition software in conjunction with word processors has shown benefits to short-term-memory restrengthening in brain AVM patients who have been treated with resection.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Further research needs to be conducted to determine cognitive benefits for individuals whose AVMs have been treated using radiologic techniques.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Substantial efforts have been devoted to the test and evaluation of speech recognition in fighter aircraft.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Of particular note have been the US programme in speech recognition for the Advanced Fighter Technology Integration (AFTI)/F-16 aircraft (F-16 VISTA), the programme in France for Mirage aircraft, and UK programmes dealing with a variety of aircraft platforms.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In these programmes, speech recognizers have been operated successfully, with applications including setting radio frequencies, commanding an autopilot system, setting steer-point coordinates and weapons release parameters, and controlling flight display.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Working with Swedish pilots flying the JAS-39 Gripen, Englund (2004) reported that recognition deteriorated with increasing g-loads.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The study concluded that adaptation greatly improved the results in all cases and that the introduction of models for breathing was shown to improve recognition scores significantly.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Contrary to what might have been expected, no effects of the broken English of the speakers were found.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Spontaneous speech caused problems for the recognizer, as might have been expected.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] A restricted vocabulary, and above all, a proper syntax, could thus be expected to improve recognition accuracy substantially.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The Eurofighter Typhoon employs a speaker-dependent system, requiring each pilot to create a template.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The system is not used for safety-critical or weapon-critical tasks, such as weapon release or lowering of the undercarriage, but is used for many cockpit functions.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Voice commands are confirmed by visual and/or aural feedback.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The system is seen as a major benefit in the reduction of pilot workload, and allows the pilot to assign targets with two voice commands or to a wingman with only five commands.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speaker-independent systems are under test for the F-35 Lightning II (JSF) and the Alenia Aermacchi M-346 Master lead-in fighter trainer.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] These systems have produced word accuracy scores in excess of 98%.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The problems of achieving high recognition accuracy under stress and noise are particularly relevant in the helicopter environment as well as in the fighter environment.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The acoustic noise problem is actually more severe in the helicopter environment, because of the high noise levels, and because helicopter pilots, in general, do not wear a facemask, which would reduce acoustic noise in the microphone.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Substantial test and evaluation programmes, notably by the U.S.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Army Avionics Research and Development Activity (AVRADA) and by the Royal Aerospace Establishment (RAE) in the UK.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Work in France included speech recognition in the Puma helicopter.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Voice applications include control of communication radios, navigation systems, and an automated target handover system.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The overriding issue for voice is the impact on pilot effectiveness.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Encouraging results are reported for the AVRADA tests, although these represent only a feasibility demonstration in a test environment.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Much remains to be done both in speech recognition and in overall speech technology in order to consistently achieve performance improvements in operational settings.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Training for air traffic controllers (ATC) represents an excellent application for speech recognition systems.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Many ATC training systems currently require a trainer to act as a "pseudo-pilot", engaging in a voice dialog with the trainee controller, which simulates the dialog that the controller would have with real pilots.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech recognition and synthesis techniques offer the potential to eliminate the need for a person to act as a pseudo-pilot, thus reducing training and support personnel.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In theory, air controller tasks are characterized by highly structured speech as the primary output, reducing the difficulty of the speech recognition task.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] FAA document 7110.65 details the phrases that should be used by air traffic controllers.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] While this document gives less than 150 examples of such phrases, the number of phrases supported by one of the simulation vendors speech recognition systems is in excess of 500,000.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The USAF, USMC, US Army, US Navy, and FAA as well as international ATC training organizations such as the Royal Australian Air Force and Civil Aviation Authorities in Italy, Brazil, and Canada use ATC simulators with speech recognition.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech recognition programs can provide many benefit to those with disabilities.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] For individuals who are deaf or hard of hearing, speech recognition software can be used to generate captions of conversations.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Additionally, individuals who are blind (see blindness and education) or have poor vision can benefit from listening to textual content, as well as garner more functionality from a computer by issuing commands with their voice.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The use of voice recognition software, in conjunction with a digital audio recorder and a personal computer running word-processing software, has proven useful for restoring damaged short-term memory capacity in individuals who have suffered a stroke or have undergone a craniotomy.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech recognition has proven very useful for those who have difficulty using their hands due to causes ranging from mild repetitive stress injuries to disabilities that preclude the use of conventional computer input devices.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Individuals with physical disabilities can use voice commands and transcription to navigate electronics hands-free.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In fact, people who developed RSI from keyboard use became an early and urgent market for speech recognition.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech recognition is used in deaf telephony, such as voicemail to text, relay services, and captioned telephone.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Individuals with learning disabilities who struggle with thought-to-paper communication may benefit from the software, but the product's fallibility remains a significant consideration for many.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In addition, speech to text technology is only an effective aid for those with intellectual disabilities if the proper training and resources are provided (e.g. in the classroom setting).
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] This type of technology can help those with dyslexia and other learning disabilities.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech-to-text has been found to improve the writing quality of students with learning disabilities.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] When compared to handwriting samples, students with learning disabilities who used speech-to-text were found to write faster and to have longer, more complex sentences with less errors.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Self esteem of young students with learning disabilities was found to rise when using speech to text due to decreased levels of anxiety associated with writing.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Students make less mistakes when using the software compared to handwriting which makes them more confident in their writing.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Mistakes made by the software hinder its effectiveness, since misheard words take more time to fix.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The act of having to go back and revise misheard words helps students to see and fix their mistakes.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] This has been shown to increase error recognition skills for users.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] ASR is now commonplace in the field of telephony.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In telephony systems, ASR is predominantly used in contact centers by integrating it with IVR systems.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] It is becoming more widespread in computer gaming and simulation.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Despite the high level of integration with word processing in general personal computing, in the field of document production, ASR has not seen the expected increases in use.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The improvement of mobile processor speeds has made speech recognition practical in smartphones.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech is used mostly as a part of a user interface, for creating predefined or custom speech commands.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The performance of speech recognition systems is usually evaluated in terms of accuracy and speed.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Accuracy is usually rated with word error rate (WER), whereas speed is measured in elapsed time.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Other measures of accuracy include Single Word Error Rate (SWER) and Command Success Rate (CSR).
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech recognition is complicated by many properties of speech.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Vocalizations vary in terms of accent, pronunciation, articulation, roughness, dialect, nasality, pitch, volume, and speed.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech is distorted by background noise, echoes, and recording characteristics.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] e.g. the 10 digits "zero" to "nine" can be recognized essentially perfectly, but vocabulary sizes of 200, 5000, or 100000 may have error rates of 3%, 7%, or 45% respectively.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] are difficult to discriminate because they are confusing words (most notoriously, the E-set: "B, C, D, E, G, P, T, V, Z (when "Z" is pronounced "zee" rather than "zed", depending on region); an 8% error rate is considered good for this vocabulary.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech recognition is a multi-level pattern recognition task.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] This hierarchy of constraints improves accuracy.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] By combining decisions probabilistically at all lower levels, and making ultimate decisions only at the highest level, speech recognition is broken into several phases.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Computationally, it is a problem in which a sound pattern has to be recognized or classified into a category that represents a meaning to a human.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Every acoustic signal can be broken into smaller sub-signals.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] As the more complex sound signal is divided, different levels are created, where at the top level are complex sounds made of simpler sounds on the lower level, etc.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] At the lowest level, simple and more probabilistic rules apply.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] These sounds are put together into more complex sounds on upper level, a new set of more deterministic rules predicts what the complex sound represents.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The upper level of a deterministic rule should figure out the meaning of complex expressions.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] In order to expand our knowledge about speech recognition, we need to take into consideration neural networks.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Sound is produced by air (or some other medium) vibration.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Sound creates a wave that has two measures: amplitude (strength), and frequency (vibrations per second).
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Accuracy can be computed with the help of WER, which is calculated by aligning the recognized word and referenced word using dynamic string alignment.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The problem may occur while computing the WER due to the difference between the sequence lengths of the recognized word and referenced word.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] where *s* is the number of substitutions, *d* is the number of deletions, *i* is the number of insertions, and *n* is the number of word references.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] While computing, the word recognition rate (WRR) is used.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Speech recognition can become a means of attack, theft, or accidental operation.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] For example, activation words like "Alexa" spoken in an audio or video broadcast can cause devices in homes and offices to start listening for input inappropriately, or possibly take an unwanted action.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Voice-controlled devices may be accessible to unauthorized users.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Attackers may be able to gain access to personal information, like calendars, address book contents, private messages, and documents.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] They may also be able to impersonate the user to send messages or make online purchases.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Two attacks have been demonstrated that use artificial sounds.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] One transmits ultrasound and attempts to send commands without people noticing.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The other adds small, inaudible distortions to other speech or music that are specially crafted to confuse the specific speech recognition system into recognizing music as speech, or to make what sounds like one command to a human sound like a different command to the system.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Regular conferences include SpeechTEK and SpeechTEK Europe, ICASSP, Interspeech/Eurospeech, and the IEEE ASRU.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] Conferences in the field of natural language processing, such as ACL, NAACL, EMNLP, and HLT, include papers on speech processing.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The main journal is *IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech and Language Processing*.
[src:whisper-asr/automatic-speech-recognition] The largest speech recognition-related project ongoing as of 2007 was the GALE project, which involves both speech recognition and translation components.
[src:whisper-asr/connectionist-temporal-classification] The input is a sequence of observations, and the outputs are a sequence of labels, which can include blank outputs.
[src:whisper-asr/connectionist-temporal-classification] The difficulty of training comes from there being many more observations than there are labels.
[src:whisper-asr/connectionist-temporal-classification] For example, in speech audio there can be multiple time slices which correspond to a single phoneme.
[src:whisper-asr/connectionist-temporal-classification] Since we don't know the alignment of the observed sequence with the target labels we predict a probability distribution at each time step.
[src:whisper-asr/connectionist-temporal-classification] A CTC network has a continuous output (e.g. softmax), which is fitted through training to model the probability of a label.
[src:whisper-asr/connectionist-temporal-classification] CTC does not attempt to learn boundaries and timings: Label sequences are considered equivalent if they differ only in alignment, ignoring blanks.
[src:whisper-asr/connectionist-temporal-classification] Equivalent label sequences can occur in many ways – which makes scoring a non-trivial task, but there is an efficient forward–backward algorithm for that.
[src:whisper-asr/connectionist-temporal-classification] CTC scores can then be used with the back-propagation algorithm to update the neural network weights.
[src:whisper-asr/connectionist-temporal-classification] Alternative approaches to a CTC-fitted neural network include a hidden Markov model (HMM).
[src:whisper-asr/connectionist-temporal-classification] In 2009, a Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC)-trained LSTM network was the first RNN to win pattern recognition contests when it won several competitions in connected handwriting recognition.
[src:whisper-asr/connectionist-temporal-classification] In 2014, the Chinese company Baidu used a bidirectional RNN (not an LSTM) trained on the CTC loss function to break the 2S09 Switchboard Hub5'00 speech recognition dataset benchmark without using any traditional speech processing methods.
[src:whisper-asr/connectionist-temporal-classification] In 2015, it was used in Google voice search and dictation on Android devices.
[src:whisper-asr/connectionist-temporal-classification] CTC is limited to monotonic alignment, which is not a problem for voice recognition, but may be a problem for language translation, as later words in a language A may correspond to earlier words in language B, since the word ordering is different for different languages.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI was founded in 2015 in Delaware as a nonprofit.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] A for-profit subsidiary of the nonprofit was created in 2019, and a 2025 restructuring converted the subsidiary into a PBC that is 26% owned by the nonprofit.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Microsoft previously invested over $13 billion into OpenAI, and provides Azure cloud computing resources.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In October 2025, OpenAI conducted a $6.6 billion share sale that valued the company at $500 billion.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In 2023 and 2024, OpenAI faced multiple lawsuits for alleged copyright infringement against authors and media companies whose work was used to train some of OpenAI's products.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In November 2023, OpenAI's board removed Sam Altman as CEO, citing a lack of confidence in him, but reinstated him five days later following a reconstruction of the board.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Throughout 2024, roughly half of then-employed AI safety researchers left OpenAI, citing the company's deprioritization of safety goals.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In December 2015, OpenAI was founded as the nonprofit organization OpenAI, Inc., by Elon Musk, Sam Altman, Ilya Sutskever, Greg Brockman, Trevor Blackwell, Vicki Cheung, Andrej Karpathy, Durk Kingma, John Schulman, Pamela Vagata, and Wojciech Zaremba, with Elon Musk and Sam Altman as the co-chairs.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] A total of $1 billion in capital was pledged by Elon Musk, Sam Altman, Greg Brockman, Reid Hoffman, Jessica Livingston, Peter Thiel, Amazon Web Services (AWS), and Infosys.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] However, the actual capital collected significantly lagged pledges.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] According to tax filings, only $133.2 million had been received by 2021.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Elon Musk stated in 2015 that he was partly motivated by concerns about AI safety and existential risk from artificial general intelligence.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI stated that "it's hard to fathom how much human-level AI could benefit society", and that it is equally difficult to comprehend "how much it could damage society if built or used incorrectly".
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The startup also wrote that AI "should be an extension of individual human wills and, in the spirit of liberty, as broadly and evenly distributed as possible", and that "because of AI's surprising history, it's hard to predict when human-level AI might come within reach.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] When it does, it'll be important to have a leading research institution which can prioritize a good outcome for all over its own self-interest." Co-chair Sam Altman expected a decades-long project that eventually surpasses human intelligence.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI was initially run from Brockman's living room.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] It was later headquartered at the Pioneer Building in the Mission District, San Francisco.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Brockman met with Yoshua Bengio, one of the "founding fathers" of deep learning, and drew up a list of great AI researchers.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Brockman was able to hire nine of them as the first employees in December 2015.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI did not pay AI researchers salaries comparable to those of Facebook or Google.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] It also did not pay stock options which AI researchers typically get.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Nevertheless, OpenAI spent $7 million on its first 52 employees in 2016.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In April 2016, OpenAI released a public beta of "OpenAI Gym", its platform for reinforcement learning research.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Nvidia gifted its first DGX-1 supercomputer to OpenAI in August 2016 to help it train larger and more complex AI models with the capability of reducing processing time from six days to two hours.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In December 2016, OpenAI released "Universe", a software platform for measuring and training an AI's general intelligence across the world's supply of games, websites, and other applications.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In 2019, OpenAI transitioned from nonprofit to "capped" for-profit, with the profit being capped at 100 times any investment.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI formed three subsidiaries: the holding company OpenAI LP, the holding company OpenAI GP LLC, and the capped for-profit company OpenAI Global, LLC.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The holding company OpenAI LP was owned by the nonprofit OpenAI, Inc., OpenAI employees, and investors, whereas OpenAI Global, LLC, was owned by OpenAI LP and Microsoft, the latter of which had a minority non-voting stake.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The nonprofit OpenAI, Inc., controlled OpenAI GP LLC, which in turn controlled OpenAI LP and OpenAI Global, LLC.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI stated that the capped-profit model would allow it to legally attract investment from venture funds and compensate employees with equity as competing AI companies did.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Microsoft subsequently invested $1 billion in OpenAI LP, and OpenAI's services were migrated to Microsoft Azure.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Since then, OpenAI systems have run on an Azure-based supercomputing platform.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The 2019 restructuring made the nonprofit OpenAI, Inc., the only controlling shareholder of OpenAI LP, which retained a formal fiduciary responsibility to OpenAI, Inc.'s nonprofit charter.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] A majority of OpenAI, Inc.'s board was barred from having financial stakes in OpenAI LP.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In addition, minority members with a stake in OpenAI LP were barred from certain votes due to conflict of interest.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Some researchers have argued that OpenAI's switch to for-profit status was inconsistent with OpenAI's claims to be "democratizing" AI.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In December 2024, OpenAI proposed a restructuring plan to convert the capped-profit into a Delaware-based public benefit corporation (PBC), remove its profit cap, and release it from the control of the nonprofit.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The nonprofit would sell its control and other assets, getting equity in return, and would use it to fund and pursue separate charitable projects, including in science and education.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI's leadership described the change as necessary to secure additional investments, and claimed that the nonprofit's founding mission to ensure AGI "benefits all of humanity" would be better fulfilled.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The plan has been criticized by former employees.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] A legal letter named "Not For Private Gain" asked the attorneys general of California and Delaware to intervene, stating that the restructuring is illegal and would remove governance safeguards from the nonprofit and the attorneys general.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The letter argues that OpenAI's complex structure was deliberately designed to remain accountable to its mission, without the conflicting pressure of maximizing profits.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] It contends that the nonprofit is best positioned to advance its mission of ensuring AGI benefits all of humanity by continuing to control OpenAI Global, LLC, whatever the amount of equity that it could get in exchange.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] PBCs can choose how they balance their mission with profit-making.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Controlling shareholders have a large influence on how closely a PBC sticks to its mission.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI subpoenaed six nonprofit organizations that opposed its for-profit transition, which the organizations described as an attempt to silence them.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On October 28, 2025, OpenAI announced that it had adopted the new PBC corporate structure after receiving approval from the attorneys general of California and Delaware.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Under the new structure, OpenAI's for-profit branch became a public benefit corporation known as OpenAI Group PBC, while the nonprofit was renamed to the OpenAI Foundation.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The OpenAI Foundation holds a 26% stake in the PBC, while Microsoft holds a 27% stake and the remaining 47% is owned by employees and other investors.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] All members of the OpenAI Group PBC board of directors are to be appointed by the OpenAI Foundation, which can remove them at any time.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] As of April 2026, all but one of the board members of the OpenAI Foundation were also board members of OpenAI Group PBC.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In April 2026, co-founder Musk revised his lawsuit against OpenAI and Altman to seek the reversal of OpenAI's corporate restructuring.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Musk lost the lawsuit in May 2026, with the jury concluding that he waited beyond the three-year statute of limitations to sue OpenAI.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Also in May 2026, *Bloomberg* reported that OpenAI was preparing to confidentially file its IPO, seeking to publicly debut in the Fall of that same year.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Following its original $1 billion investment in 2019, Microsoft invested another $2 billion through 2022.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On January 23, 2023, Microsoft announced an additional US$10 billion investment in OpenAI over multiple years, of which a significant portion would be used to purchase compute on Microsoft Azure.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] These investments were made at a $29 billion valuation, double OpenAI's 2021 valuation.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Later that year, Microsoft began using OpenAI models for its Copilot chatbot, integrated Copilot into Windows, and released mobile Copilot apps.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Following OpenAI's 2025 restructuring, Microsoft owned a 27% stake in the for-profit OpenAI Group PBC, valued at $135 billion.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In a deal announced the same day, OpenAI agreed to purchase $250 billion of Azure services, with Microsoft ceding their right of first refusal over OpenAI's future cloud computing purchases.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] As part of the deal, OpenAI will continue to share 20% of its revenue with Microsoft until it achieves AGI, which must now be verified by an independent panel of experts.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The deal also loosened restrictions on both companies working with third parties, allowing Microsoft to pursue AGI independently and allowing OpenAI to develop products with other companies.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In April 2026, the two firms announced a new agreement which removed many of the more restrictive aspects of their partnership.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] No longer the exclusive cloud provider, Microsoft then had the first right to provide cloud services, but OpenAI could purchase other services in the event that Microsoft did not provide sufficient capacity.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI will no longer receive a portion of Microsoft's revenue from using OpenAI's technology.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The artificial general intelligence clause which created uncertainty for Microsoft in the event OpenAI determined that they had created AGI was dropped.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In 2017, OpenAI spent $7.9 million, a quarter of its functional expenses, on cloud computing alone.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In comparison, DeepMind's total expenses in 2017 were $442 million.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In the summer of 2018, training OpenAI's *Dota 2* bots required renting 128,000 CPUs and 256 GPUs from Google for multiple weeks.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Microsoft's 2019 investment in OpenAI, totaling $1 billion, reportedly kicked off the "contemporary AI boom".
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In October 2024, OpenAI completed a $6.6 billion capital raise with a $157 billion valuation including investments from Microsoft, Nvidia, and SoftBank.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On January 21, 2025, Donald Trump announced The Stargate Project, a joint venture between OpenAI, Oracle, SoftBank and MGX to build an AI infrastructure system in conjunction with the US government.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The project takes its name from OpenAI's existing "Stargate" supercomputer project and is estimated to cost $500 billion.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The partners planned to fund the project over the next four years.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In July, the United States Department of Defense announced that OpenAI had received a $200 million contract for AI in the military, along with Anthropic, Google, and xAI.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In the same month, the company made a deal with the UK Government to use ChatGPT and other AI tools in public services.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI subsequently began a $50 million fund to support nonprofit and community organizations.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In April 2025, OpenAI raised $40 billion at a $300 billion post-money valuation, which was the highest-value private technology deal in history.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The financing round was led by SoftBank, with other participants including Microsoft, Coatue, Altimeter and Thrive.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In July 2025, the company reported annualized revenue of $12 billion.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] This was an increase from $3.7 billion in 2024, which was driven by ChatGPT subscriptions, which reached 20 million paid subscribers by April 2025, up from 15.5 million at the end of 2024, alongside a rapidly expanding enterprise customer base that grew to five million business users.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In February 2026, OpenAI raised $110 billion at a $730 billion valuation, led by Amazon ($50 billion), SoftBank ($30 billion), and Nvidia ($30 billion), surpassing the prior round as the largest private technology fundraise in history.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The round was later extended to $120 billion in March 2026.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In April 2026, the company announced that it closed a funding round of $122 billion in committed capital at a post-money valuation of $852 billion.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The for-profit structure established in 2025 allows the PBC to raise investor funds like most traditional tech companies, including through an initial public offering (IPO), which Altman claimed was the most likely path forward.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On June 8, 2026, OpenAI confirmed it filed for an IPO with the US Securities and Exchange.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI uses a tiered revenue model that combines free consumer access, paid subscription services, enterprise licensing, and application programming interface (API) usage-based pricing.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The basic functionality is provided at no cost, while advanced capabilities are offered through paid plans such as ChatGPT Plus and enterprise solutions.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI's subscription and enterprise offerings are structured around scalable compute usage and API integration into third-party platforms.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In 2025, the company reported significant revenue growth associated with expanded computing infrastructure and enterprise adoption.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The company's cash burn remains high because of the intensive computational costs required to train and operate large language models.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] It projects an $8 billion operating loss in 2025.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI reports revised long-term spending projections totaling approximately $115 billion through 2029, with annual expenditures projected to escalate significantly, reaching $17 billion in 2026, $35 billion in 2027, and $45 billion in 2028.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The company's financial strategy prioritizes market expansion and technological advancement over near-term profitability, with OpenAI's 2025 forecast predicting cash-flow-positive operations by 2029 and projecting revenue of approximately $200 billion by 2030.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In October 2025, OpenAI completed an employee share sale of up to $10 billion to existing investors which valued the company at $500 billion.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The deal valued OpenAI as the most valuable privately owned company in the world—surpassing SpaceX as the world's most valuable private company.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In April 2026, reports indicated that OpenAI projected approximately $2.5 billion in advertising revenue for the year, with estimates rising to $100 billion annually by 2030, highlighting advertising as a key component of its future business strategy.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In June 2026, it was announced that OpenAI and the White House have been in ongoing talks for about a year to allow a possible government stake in the company.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In August 2023, it was announced that OpenAI had acquired the New York-based start-up Global Illumination, a company that deploys AI to develop digital infrastructure and creative tools.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In June 2024, OpenAI acquired Multi, a startup focused on remote collaboration.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On February 10, 2025, a consortium of investors led by Elon Musk submitted a $97.4 billion unsolicited bid to buy the nonprofit that controls OpenAI, declaring willingness to match or exceed any better offer.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The offer was rejected on 14 February 2025, with OpenAI stating that it was not for sale, but the offer complicated Altman's restructuring plan by suggesting a lower bar for how much the nonprofit should be valued.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In March 2025, OpenAI reached a deal with CoreWeave to acquire $350 million worth of CoreWeave shares and access to AI infrastructure, in return for $11.9 billion paid over five years.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Microsoft was already CoreWeave's biggest customer in 2024.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Alongside their other business dealings, OpenAI and Microsoft were renegotiating the terms of their partnership to facilitate a potential future IPO by OpenAI, while ensuring Microsoft's continued access to advanced AI models.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On May 21, 2025 OpenAI announced the $6.5 billion acquisition of io, an AI hardware start-up founded by former Apple designer Jony Ive in 2024.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In September 2025, OpenAI agreed to acquire the product testing startup Statsig for $1.1 billion in an all-stock deal and appointed Statsig's founding CEO Vijaye Raji as OpenAI's chief technology officer of applications.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The company also announced development of an AI-driven hiring service designed to rival LinkedIn.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI acquired personal finance app Roi in October 2025.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In October 2025, OpenAI acquired Software Applications Incorporated, the developer of Sky, a macOS-based natural language interface designed to operate across desktop applications.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The Sky team joined OpenAI, and the company announced plans to integrate Sky's capabilities into ChatGPT.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In December 2025, it was announced OpenAI had agreed to acquire Neptune, an AI tooling startup that helps companies track and manage model training, for an undisclosed amount.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In January 2026, it was announced OpenAI had acquired healthcare technology startup Torch for approximately $60 million.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The acquisition followed the launch of OpenAI's ChatGPT Health product and was intended to strengthen the company's medical data and healthcare artificial intelligence capabilities.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI acquired Python tool developer Astral in March 2026.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In April 2026, the company acquired TBPN, a media company in California, for an undisclosed sum.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI has been criticized for outsourcing the annotation of data sets to Sama, a company based in San Francisco that employed workers in Kenya.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] These annotations were used to train an AI model to detect toxicity, which could then be used to moderate toxic content, notably from ChatGPT's training data and outputs.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] However, these pieces of text usually contained detailed descriptions of various types of violence, including sexual violence.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI began sending snippets of data to Sama as early as November 2021.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The four Sama employees interviewed by *Time* described themselves as mentally scarred.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI paid Sama $12.50 per hour of work, and Sama was redistributing the equivalent of between $1.32 and $2.00 per hour post-tax to its annotators.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Sama's spokesperson said that the $12.50 was also covering other implicit costs, among which were infrastructure expenses, quality assurance and management.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In 2024, OpenAI began collaborating with Broadcom to design a custom AI chip capable of both training and inference, targeted for mass production in 2026 and to be manufactured by TSMC on a 3 nm process node.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] This initiative intended to reduce OpenAI's dependence on Nvidia GPUs, which are costly and face high demand in the market.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In January 2024, Arizona State University purchased ChatGPT Enterprise in OpenAI's first deal with a university.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In June 2024, Apple Inc. signed a contract with OpenAI to integrate ChatGPT features into its products as part of its new Apple Intelligence initiative.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In December 2024, OpenAI partnered with Anduril Industries to develop and deploy advanced artificial intelligence solutions for national security missions.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In June 2025, OpenAI began renting Google Cloud's Tensor Processing Units (TPUs) to support ChatGPT and related services, marking its first meaningful use of non‑Nvidia AI chips.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In September 2025, it was revealed that OpenAI signed a contract with Oracle to purchase $300 billion in computing power over the next five years.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In September 2025, OpenAI and NVIDIA announced a memorandum of understanding that included a potential deployment of at least 10 gigawatts of NVIDIA systems and a $100 billion investment from NVIDIA in OpenAI.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI expected the negotiations to be completed within weeks.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] As of January 2026, this has not been realized, and the two sides are rethinking the future of their partnership.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In October 2025, OpenAI announced a multi-billion dollar deal with AMD.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI committed to purchasing six gigawatts worth of AMD chips, starting with the MI450.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI will have the option to buy up to 160 million shares of AMD, about 10% of the company, depending on development, performance and share price targets.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In December 2025, Disney said it would make a $1 billion investment in OpenAI, and signed a three-year licensing deal that will let users generate videos using Sora—OpenAI's short-form AI video platform.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] More than 200 Disney, Marvel, Star Wars and Pixar characters would be available to OpenAI users.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Disney would later exit this deal in late March 2026, due to Sora being discontinued.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In early 2026, Amazon entered advanced discussions to invest up to $50 billion in OpenAI as part of a potential artificial intelligence partnership.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Under the proposed agreement, OpenAI's models could be integrated into Amazon's digital assistant Alexa and other internal projects.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In June 2026, OpenAI announced partnerships with Wix, Base44, Replit, Lovable, Figma, and Emergent to support its new Sites feature in Codex, which enables users to publish outputs as hosted, interactive websites rather than local files.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On June 24, 2026, OpenAI announced its new chip called Jalapeño, created in collaboration with Broadcom.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The company plans to start rolling it out by the end of 2026.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI provides LLMs to the Artificial Intelligence Cyber Challenge and to the Advanced Research Projects Agency for Health.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In October 2024, The Intercept revealed that OpenAI's tools are considered "essential" for AFRICOM's mission and included in an "Exception to Fair Opportunity" contractual agreement between the United States Department of Defense (DoD) and Microsoft.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In December 2024, OpenAI said it would partner with defense-tech company Anduril to build drone defense technologies for the United States and its allies.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In 2025, OpenAI's Chief Product Officer, Kevin Weil, was commissioned lieutenant colonel in the U.S.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Army to join Detachment 201 as senior advisor.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In June 2025, the DoD awarded OpenAI a $200 million one-year contract to develop AI tools for military and national security applications.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI announced a new program, OpenAI for Government, to give federal, state, and local governments access to its models, including ChatGPT.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On 28 February 2026, after OpenAI's competitor Anthropic refused to authorize the DoD to use its AI systems for mass surveillance or autonomous weapons systems, it was labeled a "supply-chain risk" by the DoD and the Trump administration decided to stop using it across the government.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The same day, OpenAI announced that it had reached an agreement with the DoD to deploy its models in the government's classified network.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] CEO Sam Altman wrote, "Two of our most important safety principles are prohibitions on domestic mass surveillance and human responsibility for the use of force, including for autonomous weapon systems", that the DoD agrees with this, and that this is included in their agreement.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] However, while the agreement mentioned existing law and allowed OpenAI to implement some technical safeguards, it did not incorporate legally binding prohibitions on domestic mass surveillance or fully autonomous weapons.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Following backlash over the potential use of ChatGPT for surveillance, Altman amended the contract to include more safeguards, though only excerpts of the contract were made public and critics remained concerned that it was purposefully vague and contained carve-outs for domestic surveillance.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In February 2019, GPT-2 was announced, which gained attention for its ability to generate human-like text.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In 2020, OpenAI announced GPT-3, a language model trained on large internet datasets.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] GPT-3 is aimed at natural language answering questions, but it can also translate between languages and coherently generate improvised text.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] It also announced that an associated API, named *the API*, would form the heart of its first commercial product.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Eleven employees left OpenAI, mostly between December 2020 and January 2021, in order to establish Anthropic.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In 2021, OpenAI introduced DALL-E, a specialized deep learning model adept at generating complex digital images from textual descriptions, utilizing a variant of the GPT-3 architecture.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In December 2022, OpenAI received widespread media coverage after launching a free preview of ChatGPT, its new AI chatbot based on GPT-3.5.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] According to OpenAI, the preview received over a million signups within the first five days.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] According to anonymous sources cited by Reuters in December 2022, OpenAI Global, LLC was projecting $200 million of revenue in 2023 and $1 billion in revenue in 2024.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] After ChatGPT was launched, Google announced a similar chatbot, Bard, amid internal concerns that ChatGPT could threaten Google's position as a primary source of online information.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On February 7, 2023, Microsoft announced that it was building AI technology based on the same foundation as ChatGPT into Microsoft Bing, Edge, Microsoft 365 and other products.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On March 14, 2023, OpenAI released GPT-4, both as an API (with a waitlist) and as a feature of ChatGPT Plus.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On November 6, 2023, OpenAI launched GPTs, allowing individuals to create customized versions of ChatGPT for specific purposes, further expanding the possibilities of AI applications across various industries.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On November 14, 2023, OpenAI announced they temporarily suspended new sign-ups for ChatGPT Plus due to high demand.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Access for newer subscribers re-opened a month later on December 13.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In December 2024, the company launched the Sora model.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] It also launched OpenAI o1, an early reasoning model that was internally codenamed *strawberry*.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Additionally, ChatGPT Pro—a $200/month subscription service offering unlimited o1 access and enhanced voice features—was introduced, and preliminary benchmark results for the upcoming OpenAI o3 models were shared.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On January 23, 2025, OpenAI released Operator, an AI agent and tool for accessing websites to execute goals defined by users.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The feature was only available to Pro users in the United States.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI released deep research agent, nine days later.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] It scored a 27% accuracy on the benchmark Humanity's Last Exam (HLE).
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Altman later stated GPT-4.5 would be the last model without full chain-of-thought reasoning.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In July 2025, according to OpenAI, one of its experimental models performed at a gold medal-level at the International Mathematical Olympiad.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On October 6, 2025, OpenAI displayed its Agent Builder platform during the company's DevDay event.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The platform includes a visual drag-and-drop interface for agentic workflows.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On October 21, 2025, OpenAI introduced ChatGPT Atlas, a web browser which integrates ChatGPT into web navigation.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On December 11, 2025, OpenAI announced GPT-5.2.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In early 2026, reports indicated that OpenAI was working on a collaborative software development platform designed to compete with services such as GitHub and GitLab.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In March 2023, the company was criticized for disclosing particularly few technical details about products like GPT-4, contradicting its initial commitment to openness and making it harder for independent researchers to replicate its work and develop safeguards.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI cited competitiveness and safety concerns to justify this repudiation.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI's former chief scientist Ilya Sutskever argued in 2023 that open-sourcing increasingly capable models was increasingly risky, and that the safety reasons for not open-sourcing the most potent AI models would become "obvious" in a few years.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In September 2025, OpenAI published a study on how people use ChatGPT for everyday tasks.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The study found that "non-work tasks" (according to an LLM-based classifier) account for more than 72 percent of all ChatGPT usage, with a minority of overall usage related to business productivity.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In July 2023, OpenAI launched the superalignment project, aiming within four years to determine how to align future superintelligent systems.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI promised to dedicate 20% of its computing resources to the project, although the company's employees later reported that the company only allocated 1–2% of its resources to it.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI ended the project in May 2024 after its co-leaders Ilya Sutskever and Jan Leike left the company.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In August 2025, OpenAI was criticized after thousands of private ChatGPT conversations were inadvertently exposed to public search engines like Google due to an experimental "share with search engines" feature.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The opt-in toggle, intended to allow users to make specific chats discoverable, resulted in some discussions including personal details such as names, locations, and intimate topics appearing in search results when users accidentally enabled it while sharing links.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI announced the feature's permanent removal on August 1, 2025, and the company began coordinating with search providers to remove the exposed content, emphasizing that it was not a security breach but a design flaw that heightened privacy risks.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] CEO Sam Altman acknowledged the issue in a podcast, noting users often treat ChatGPT as a confidant for deeply personal matters, which amplified concerns about AI handling sensitive data.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On November 17, 2023, Sam Altman was removed as CEO when OpenAI's board of directors (composed of Helen Toner, Ilya Sutskever, Adam D'Angelo and Tasha McCauley) cited a lack of confidence in him.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Chief Technology Officer Mira Murati took over as interim CEO.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Greg Brockman, the president of OpenAI, was also removed as chairman of the board and resigned from the company's presidency shortly thereafter.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Three senior OpenAI researchers subsequently resigned: director of research and GPT-4 lead Jakub Pachocki, head of AI risk Aleksander Mądry, and researcher Szymon Sidor.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On November 18, 2023, there were reportedly talks of Altman returning as CEO amid pressure placed upon the board by investors such as Microsoft and Thrive Capital, who objected to Altman's departure.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Although Altman himself spoke in favor of returning to OpenAI, he has since stated that he considered starting a new company and bringing former OpenAI employees with him if talks to reinstate him did not work out.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Altman insisted multiple times that all board members who supported his removal should resign; the board members agreed "in principle" to resign if Altman returned.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On November 19, 2023, negotiations with Altman to return failed and Murati was replaced by Emmett Shear as interim CEO.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] The board initially contacted Anthropic CEO Dario Amodei (a former OpenAI executive) about replacing Altman, and proposed a merger of the two companies, but both offers were declined.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On November 20, 2023, Microsoft CEO Satya Nadella announced Altman and Brockman would be joining Microsoft to lead a new advanced AI research team, but added that they were still committed to OpenAI despite recent events.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Before the partnership with Microsoft was finalized, Altman gave the board another opportunity to negotiate with him.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] About 738 of OpenAI's 770 employees, including Murati and Sutskever, signed an open letter stating they would quit their jobs and join Microsoft if the board did not rehire Altman and then resign.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] This prompted OpenAI investors to consider legal action against the board as well.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In response, OpenAI management sent an internal memo to employees stating that negotiations with Altman and the board had resumed and would take some time.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On November 21, 2023, after continued negotiations, Altman and Brockman returned to the company in their prior roles along with a reconstructed board made up of new members Bret Taylor (as chairman) and Lawrence Summers, with D'Angelo remaining.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] According to subsequent reporting, shortly before Altman's firing, some employees raised concerns to the board about how he had handled the safety implications of a recent internal AI capability discovery.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On November 29, 2023, OpenAI announced that an anonymous Microsoft employee had joined the board as a non-voting member to observe the company's operations; Microsoft resigned from the board in July 2024.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In February 2024, the Securities and Exchange Commission subpoenaed OpenAI's internal communication to determine if Altman's alleged lack of candor misled investors.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Following the temporary removal of Sam Altman and his return, many employees gradually left OpenAI, including most of the original leadership team and a significant number of AI safety researchers.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In 2018, Musk resigned from his Board of Directors seat, citing "a potential future conflict [of interest]" with his role as CEO of Tesla due to Tesla's AI development for self-driving cars.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI stated that Musk's financial contributions were below $45 million.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] On March 3, 2023, Reid Hoffman resigned from his board seat, citing a desire to avoid conflicts of interest with his investments in AI companies via Greylock Partners, and his co-founding of the AI startup Inflection AI.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Hoffman remained on the board of Microsoft, a major investor in OpenAI.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In May 2024, Chief Scientist Ilya Sutskever resigned and was succeeded by Jakub Pachocki.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Co-leader Jan Leike also departed amid concerns over safety and trust.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] OpenAI then signed deals with Reddit, News Corp, Axios, and Vox Media.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Paul Nakasone then joined the board of OpenAI.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In August 2024, cofounder John Schulman left OpenAI to join Anthropic, and OpenAI's president Greg Brockman took extended leave until November.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In September 2024, CTO Mira Murati left the company.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In November 2025, Lawrence Summers resigned from the board of directors.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] In April 2026, OpenAI's head of AGI deployment, Fidji Simo, said she would take "several weeks" of medical leave.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] This triggered a reshuffling of the leadership.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Brad Lightcap transitioned from his role as Chief Operating Officer to lead "special projects" focused on complex deals, reporting directly to Sam Altman.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] This includes a potential software distribution joint venture with private equity partners.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p01] Denise Dresser, the company's Chief Revenue Officer, temporarily assumed several of Lightcap's previous operational duties, with Greg Brockman taking over the product organization.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In May 2023, Sam Altman, Greg Brockman and Ilya Sutskever posted recommendations for the governance of superintelligence.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] They stated that superintelligence could happen within the next 10 years, allowing a "dramatically more prosperous future" and that "given the possibility of existential risk, we can't just be reactive".
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] They proposed creating an international watchdog organization similar to IAEA to oversee AI systems above a certain capability threshold, suggesting that relatively weak AI systems, on the other hand, should not be overly regulated.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] They also called for more technical safety research for superintelligences, and asked for more coordination, for example through governments launching a joint project which "many current efforts become part of".
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In July 2023, the FTC issued a civil investigative demand to OpenAI to investigate whether the company's data security and privacy practices to develop ChatGPT were unfair or harmed consumers (including by reputational harm) in violation of Section 5 of the Federal Trade Commission Act of 1914.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] These are typically preliminary investigative matters and are nonpublic, but the FTC's document was leaked.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] They asked OpenAI for comprehensive information about its technology and privacy safeguards, as well as any steps taken to prevent the recurrence of situations in which its chatbot generated false and disparaging content about people.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The agency also raised concerns about 'circular' spending arrangements—for example, Microsoft extending Azure credits to OpenAI while both companies shared engineering talent—and warned that such structures could negatively affect the public.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In September 2024, OpenAI's global affairs chief endorsed the UK's "smart" AI regulation during testimony to a House of Lords committee.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In February 2025, OpenAI CEO Sam Altman stated that the company is interested in collaborating with the People's Republic of China, despite regulatory restrictions imposed by the U.S. government.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] This shift comes in response to the growing influence of the Chinese artificial intelligence company DeepSeek, which has disrupted the AI market with open models, including DeepSeek V3 and DeepSeek R1.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Following DeepSeek's market emergence, OpenAI enhanced security protocols to protect proprietary development techniques from industrial espionage.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Some industry observers noted similarities between DeepSeek's model distillation approach and OpenAI's methodology, though no formal intellectual property claim was filed.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] According to Oliver Roberts, in March 2025, the United States had 781 state AI bills or laws.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] OpenAI advocated for preempting state AI laws with federal laws.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] According to Scott Kohler, OpenAI has opposed California's AI legislation and suggested that the state bill encroaches on a more competent federal government.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Public Citizen opposed a federal preemption on AI and pointed to OpenAI's growth and valuation as evidence that existing state laws have not hampered innovation.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In early 2026, OpenAI provided the entire initial funding for the Parents & Kids Safe AI Coalition.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Several organizations contacted on behalf of the coalition reported being unaware of OpenAI's involvement.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Before May 2024, OpenAI required departing employees to sign a lifelong non-disparagement agreement forbidding them from criticizing OpenAI or acknowledging the existence of the agreement.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Daniel Kokotajlo, a former employee, publicly stated that he forfeited his vested equity in OpenAI in order to leave without signing the agreement.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Sam Altman stated that he was unaware of the equity cancellation provision, and that OpenAI never enforced it to cancel any employee's vested equity.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] However, leaked documents and emails refute this claim.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] On May 23, 2024, OpenAI sent a memo releasing former employees from the agreement.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] OpenAI was sued for copyright infringement by authors Sarah Silverman, Matthew Butterick, Paul Tremblay and Mona Awad in July 2023.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In September 2023, 17 authors, including George R.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Martin, John Grisham, Jodi Picoult and Jonathan Franzen, joined the Authors Guild in filing a class action lawsuit against OpenAI, alleging that the company's technology was illegally using their copyrighted work.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The *New York Times* also sued the company in late December 2023.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In May 2024 it was revealed that OpenAI had destroyed its Books1 and Books2 training datasets, which were used in the training of GPT-3, and which the Authors Guild believed to have contained over 100,000 copyrighted books.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In 2021, OpenAI developed a speech recognition tool called Whisper.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] OpenAI used it to transcribe more than one million hours of YouTube videos into text for training GPT-4.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The automated transcription of YouTube videos raised concerns within OpenAI employees regarding potential violations of YouTube's terms of service, which prohibit the use of videos for applications independent of the platform, as well as any type of automated access to its videos.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Despite these concerns, the project proceeded with notable involvement from OpenAI's president, Greg Brockman.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The resulting dataset proved instrumental in training GPT-4.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In February 2024, *The Intercept* as well as *Raw Story* and Alternate Media Inc. filed lawsuit against OpenAI on copyright litigation ground.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The lawsuit is said to have charted a new legal strategy for digital-only publishers to sue OpenAI.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] On April 30, 2024, eight newspapers filed a lawsuit in the Southern District of New York against OpenAI and Microsoft, claiming illegal harvesting of their copyrighted articles.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The suing publications included *The Mercury News*, *The Denver Post*, *The Orange County Register*, *St.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Paul Pioneer Press*, *Chicago Tribune*, *Orlando Sentinel*, *Sun Sentinel*, and *New York Daily News*.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In June 2023, a lawsuit claimed that OpenAI scraped 300 billion words online without consent and without registering as a data broker.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] It was filed in San Francisco, California, by sixteen anonymous plaintiffs.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] They also claimed that OpenAI and its partner as well as customer Microsoft continued to unlawfully collect and use personal data from millions of consumers worldwide to train artificial intelligence models.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] On May 22, 2024, OpenAI entered into an agreement with News Corp to integrate news content from *The Wall Street Journal*, the *New York Post*, *The Times*, and *The Sunday Times* into its AI platform.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Meanwhile, other publications like *The New York Times* chose to sue OpenAI and Microsoft for copyright infringement over the use of their content to train AI models.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In November 2024, a coalition of Canadian news outlets, including the Toronto Star, Metroland Media, Postmedia, The Globe and Mail, The Canadian Press and CBC, sued OpenAI for using their news articles to train its software without permission.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In October 2024 during a New York Times interview, Suchir Balaji accused OpenAI of violating copyright law in developing its commercial LLMs which he had helped engineer.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] He was a likely witness in a major copyright trial against the AI company, and was one of several of its current or former employees named in court filings as potentially having documents relevant to the case.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] On November 26, 2024, Balaji died by suicide.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] His death prompted the circulation of conspiracy theories alleging that he had been deliberately silenced.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] California Congressman Ro Khanna endorsed calls for an investigation.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] On April 24, 2025, Ziff Davis sued OpenAI in Delaware federal court for copyright infringement.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Ziff Davis is known for publications such as ZDNet, PCMag, CNET, IGN and Lifehacker.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] On June 24, 2026, a group of local newspaper publishers also sued OpenAI and Microsoft for copyright infringement.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In late April 2024 NOYB filed a complaint with the Austrian Datenschutzbehörde against OpenAI for violating the European General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] A text created with ChatGPT gave a false date of birth for a living person without giving the individual the option to see the personal data used in the process.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] A request to correct the mistake was denied.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Additionally, neither the recipients of ChatGPT's work nor the sources used, could be made available, OpenAI claimed.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In Europe, OpenAI operates as OpenAI Ireland Ltd for residents in the EEA or Switzerland and OpenAI OpCo, LLC, a Delaware company for residents in the UK like in the US.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] OpenAI has been criticized for allowing ChatGPT to be used for "military and warfare" since January 10, 2024, when its "usage policies" removed the ban on "activity that has high risk of physical harm, including", specifically, "weapons development" and "military and warfare".
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Its new policies prohibit "[using] our service to harm yourself or others" and to "develop or use weapons".
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] On February 29, 2024, Elon Musk filed a lawsuit against OpenAI and CEO Sam Altman, accusing them of shifting focus from public benefit to profit maximization—a case OpenAI dismissed as "incoherent" and "frivolous", though Musk later revived legal action against Altman and others in August.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] On April 9, 2024, OpenAI countersued Musk in federal court, alleging that he had engaged in "bad-faith tactics" to slow the company's progress and seize its innovations for his personal benefit.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] OpenAI also argued that Musk had previously supported the creation of a for-profit structure and had expressed interest in controlling OpenAI himself.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The countersuit seeks damages and legal measures to prevent further alleged interference.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Musk amended his filing on April 7, 2026, to demand that OpenAI undo its transition from a non-profit to a for-profit corporate structure.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The jury for the case against OpenAI, Altman and Greg Brockman was seated on April 27, 2026.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] On April 28, 2026, trial testimony was underway, with Elon Musk beginning his testimony against Altman and OpenAI.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] On April 30, 2026 Musk would enter his third day of testimony.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] On May 18, 2026, following a federal jury verdict in favor of OpenAI, Sam Altman, Greg Brockman and Microsoft in Musk v.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In August 2025, the parents of a 16-year-old boy who died by suicide filed a wrongful death lawsuit, *Raine v.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] OpenAI*, against the company (and CEO Sam Altman), alleging that months of conversations with ChatGPT about mental health and methods of self-harm contributed to their son's death and that safeguards were inadequate for minors.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] OpenAI expressed condolences and said it was strengthening protections (including updated crisis response behavior and parental controls).
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Coverage described it as a first-of-its-kind wrongful death case targeting the company's chatbot.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The complaint was filed in California state court in San Francisco.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In November 2025, the Social Media Victims Law Center and Tech Justice Law Project filed seven lawsuits against OpenAI, of which four lawsuits alleged wrongful death.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The suits were filed on behalf of Zane Shamblin, 23, of Texas; Amaurie Lacey, 17, of Georgia; Joshua Enneking, 26, of Florida; and Joe Ceccanti, 48, of Oregon, who each committed suicide after prolonged ChatGPT usage.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In December 2025, after Suzanne Adams was murdered by her 56-year-old son, First County Bank, the executor of Adams's estate, filed a lawsuit against OpenAI.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The lawsuit alleges that over months of conversations, ChatGPT validated her son's many paranoid beliefs, such as that his mother was spying on him and that she attempted to poison him using drugs siphoned through his car air vents.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] OpenAI said they would make ChatGPT safer for users disconnected from reality.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] After 8 victims were killed on February 10, 2026, in mass shootings in Tumbler Ridge, British Columbia, it emerged that OpenAI had banned an account belonging to the perpetrator due to violent queries approximately 7 months prior to the attacks.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] OpenAI opted not to report the account to authorities at the time.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The *Wall Street Journal* reported that the perpetrator "described scenarios [to ChatGPT] involving gun violence over the course of several days", and that these messages were "flagged by an automated review system" and "alarmed employees at OpenAI".
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] A dozen employees debated whether to take action, some urging leaders to alert Canadian law enforcement.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Canadian officials summoned OpenAI's safety team to Ottawa, criticizing their escalation protocols.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The meeting highlighted concerns about how and when OpenAI reports potentially dangerous user behavior to authorities and intensified scrutiny of its safety-oversight processes.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] On February 23, BC Premier David Eby said, "From the outside, it looks like OpenAI had the opportunity to prevent this tragedy, to prevent this horrific loss of life, to prevent there from being dead children in British Columbia".
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] Canada's federal AI Minister Evan Solomon said, "I want [OpenAI] to give us details of what their protocols are, [and] what they are specifically in Canada".
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] In 2026, a woman filed a lawsuit against OpenAI, alleging that ChatGPT played a role in enabling a prolonged stalking campaign against her.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] According to the complaint, her former partner became increasingly fixated and used the chatbot to generate messages and content that reinforced his behavior, including harassing and defamatory material.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The plaintiff claimed that she had contacted OpenAI to report the issue, but that the company did not take adequate action to prevent further misuse.
[src:whisper-asr/openai-p02] The case has been cited as part of growing legal and public debate over the responsibility of AI companies to address harmful or abusive uses of their systems.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In deep learning, the **transformer** is a family of artificial neural network architectures based on the multi-head attention mechanism, in which text is converted to numerical representations called tokens, and each token is converted into a vector via lookup from a word embedding table.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At each layer, each token is then contextualized within the scope of the context window with other (unmasked) tokens via a parallel multi-head attention mechanism, allowing the signal for key tokens to be amplified and less important tokens to be diminished.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Because self-attention alone is permutation-invariant, transformers inject positional information, typically through positional encodings or learned positional embeddings, so token order can affect the output.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers have the advantage of having no recurrent units, therefore requiring less training time than earlier recurrent neural architectures (RNNs) such as long short-term memory (LSTM).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Later variations have been widely adopted for training large language models (LLMs) on large (language) datasets.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Modern transformer designs are commonly grouped into encoder-only, decoder-only, and encoder-decoder variants, depending on whether they are optimized for representation learning, autoregressive generation, or conditional sequence-to-sequence tasks.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The original version of the transformer architecture was proposed in the 2017 paper "Attention Is All You Need" by researchers at Google.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The predecessors of transformers were developed as an improvement over previous architectures for machine translation, but have found many applications since.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are used in large-scale natural language processing, computer vision (vision transformers), reinforcement learning, audio, multimodal learning, robotics, and playing chess.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It has also led to the development of pre-trained systems, such as generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) and BERT (bidirectional encoder representations from transformers).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For many years, sequence modelling and generation was done by using plain recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A well-cited early example was the Elman network (1990).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In theory, the information from one token can propagate arbitrarily far down the sequence, but in practice the vanishing-gradient problem leaves the model's state at the end of a long sentence without precise, extractable information about preceding tokens.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A key breakthrough was LSTM (originally described in a 1995 technical report and formally published in 1997), an RNN that introduced gating mechanisms to mitigate the vanishing gradient problem, allowing efficient learning of long-sequence modelling.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One key architectural element was the use of *multiplicative gating units*, in which the outputs of some neurons modulate the outputs of others.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These multiplicative units are conceptually distinct from the additive attention mechanism later introduced for sequence-to-sequence models.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Neural networks using multiplicative units were later called *sigma-pi networks* or *higher-order networks*.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] LSTM became the standard architecture for long sequence modelling until the 2017 publication of transformers.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] However, LSTM still used sequential processing, like most other RNNs.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, RNNs operate one token at a time from first to last; they cannot operate in parallel over all tokens in a sequence.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Modern transformers overcome this problem, but unlike RNNs, they require computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The linearly scaling fast weight controller (1992) learns to compute a weight matrix for further processing depending on the input.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One of its two networks has "fast weights" or "dynamic links" (1981).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A slow neural network learns by gradient descent to generate keys and values for computing the weight changes of the fast neural network which computes answers to queries.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The idea of encoder–decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s; commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two concurrently published papers from 2014.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A 380M-parameter model for machine translation uses two long short-term memories (LSTM).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *encoder* is an LSTM that takes in a sequence of tokens and turns it into a vector.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *decoder* is another LSTM that converts the vector into a sequence of tokens.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly, another 130M-parameter model used gated recurrent units (GRU) instead of LSTM.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Later research showed that GRUs are neither better nor worse than LSTMs for seq2seq.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These early seq2seq models had no attention mechanism, and the state vector is accessible only after the *last* word of the source text was processed.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Although in theory such a vector retains the information about the whole original sentence, in practice the information is poorly preserved.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is because the input is processed sequentially by one recurrent network into a *fixed*-size output vector, which is then processed by another recurrent network into an output.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the input is long, then the output vector would not be able to contain all relevant information, degrading the output.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As evidence, reversing the input sentence improved seq2seq translation.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *RNN search* model introduced an attention mechanism to seq2seq for machine translation to solve the bottleneck problem (of the *fixed-size* output vector), allowing the model to process long-distance dependencies more easily.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The name is because it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The relative performances were compared between global (that of *RNN search*) and local (sliding window) attention model architectures for machine translation, finding that mixed attention had higher quality than global attention, while local attention reduced translation time.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2016, Google Translate was revamped to Google Neural Machine Translation, which replaced the previous model based on statistical machine translation.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The new model was a seq2seq model where the encoder and the decoder were both 8 layers of bidirectional LSTM.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It took nine months to develop, and it outperformed the statistical approach, which took ten years to develop.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Seq2seq models with attention (including self-attention) still suffered from the same issue with recurrent networks, which is that they are hard to parallelize, which prevented them from being accelerated on GPUs.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2016, *decomposable attention* applied a self-attention mechanism to feedforward networks, which are easy to parallelize, and achieved SOTA result in textual entailment with an order of magnitude fewer parameters than LSTMs.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One of its authors, Jakob Uszkoreit, suspected that attention *without* recurrence would be sufficient for language translation, thus the title "attention is *all* you need".
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] That hypothesis was against conventional wisdom at the time, and even his father Hans Uszkoreit, a well-known computational linguist, was skeptical.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the same year, self-attention (called *intra-attention or* *intra-sentence attention*) was proposed for LSTMs.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] On 2017-06-12, the original (100M-parameter) encoder–decoder transformer model was published in the "Attention is all you need" paper.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At the time, the focus of the research was on improving seq2seq for machine translation, by removing its recurrence to process all tokens in parallel, but preserving its dot-product attention mechanism to keep its text processing performance.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This led to the introduction of a multi-head attention model that was easier to parallelize due to the use of independent heads and the lack of recurrence.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Its parallelizability was an important factor to its widespread use in large neural networks.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As early as spring 2017, even before the "Attention is all you need" preprint was published, one of the co-authors applied the "decoder-only" variation of the architecture to generate fictitious Wikipedia articles.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformer architecture is now used alongside many generative models that contribute to the ongoing AI boom.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The "reference implementation" of the original Transformer was written in a TensorFlow library.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In language modelling, ELMo (2018) was a bi-directional LSTM that produces contextualized word embeddings, improving upon the line of research from bag of words and word2vec.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It was followed by BERT (2018), an encoder-only transformer model.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In October 2019, Google started using BERT to process search queries.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model by a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Starting in 2018, the OpenAI GPT series of decoder-only transformers became state of the art in natural language generation.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At the end of 2022, ChatGPT, a chatbot based on a fine-tuned variant of GPT-3.5, became unexpectedly popular, triggering a boom around large language models.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers have been applied in modalities beyond text.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Four days after the publication of "Attention is All You Need", a multimodal transformer architecture, MultiModel, was published by most authors of that paper.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Other examples include the vision transformer, speech recognition, robotics, and multimodal.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The vision transformer, in turn, stimulated new developments in convolutional neural networks.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The plain transformer architecture had difficulty in converging.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the original paper, the authors recommended using learning rate warmup.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] That is, the learning rate should linearly scale up from 0 to maximal value for the first part of the training (usually recommended to be 2% of the total number of training steps), before decaying again.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A 2020 paper found that using layer normalization *before* (instead of after) multihead attention and feedforward layers stabilizes training, not requiring learning rate warmup.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is the "pre-LN Transformer" and is more commonly used, compared to the original "post-LN Transformer".
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers typically are first pretrained by self-supervised learning on a large generic dataset, followed by supervised fine-tuning on a small task-specific dataset.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The pretrain dataset is typically an unlabeled large corpus, such as The Pile.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The T5 transformer report documents a large number of natural language pretraining tasks.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Note that while each of these tasks is trivial or obvious for human native speakers of the language (or languages), they have typically proved challenging for previous generations of machine learning architecture.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In general, there are 3 classes of language modelling tasks: "masked", "autoregressive", and "prefixLM".
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These classes are independent of a specific modeling architecture such as transformer, but they are often discussed in the context of transformer.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In a masked task, one or more of the tokens is masked out, and the model would produce a probability distribution predicting what the masked-out tokens are based on the context.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The loss function for the task is typically sum of log-perplexities for the masked-out tokens: ${\text{Loss}}=-\sum _{t\in {\text{masked tokens}}}\ln({\text{probability of }}t{\text{ conditional on its context}})$ and the model is trained to minimize this loss function.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The BERT series of models are trained for masked token prediction and another task.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In an autoregressive task, the entire sequence is masked at first, and the model produces a probability distribution for the first token.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then the first token is revealed and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The loss function for the task is still typically the same.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The GPT series of models are trained by autoregressive tasks.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In a prefixLM task, the sequence is divided into two parts.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The first part is presented as context, and the model predicts the first token of the second part.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then that would be revealed, and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The T5 series of models are trained by prefixLM tasks.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Note that "masked" as in "masked language modelling" is not "masked" as in "masked attention", and "prefixLM" as in "prefix language modeling" is not "prefixLM" as in " prefix language model".
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The following description follows exactly the transformer as described in the original paper.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There are variants, described in the following section.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] By convention, we write all vectors as row vectors.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, pushing a vector through a linear layer means multiplying it by a weight matrix on the right, as $xW$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As the transformer architecture natively consists of operations over numbers (matrix multiplications, dot products, activation functions) rather than over text, there must first be a mapping from any input text to some numerical representation.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] First, the input text is treated by a *preprocessor*, which performs both textual transformations and splits the text into coarse-grained segments called *pretokens*.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The latter is referred to as *pretokenization*.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Second, each pretoken is segmented further into *tokens* by a *tokenizer* that expects to only see pretokens output by its preprocessor.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each token it produces is a string of one or more characters belonging to a finite set of strings called the *vocabulary* V .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Third, because the vocabulary is finite and known beforehand, each token can be assigned an integer identifier, and this mapping is applied to the sequence of tokens to represent any input text as a numerical sequence.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Since this mapping is bijective, the output side can produce a sequence of integer identifiers which can then be turned back into tokens.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] After undoing some of the preprocessing, the result is again legible text.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Training a tokenizer (sometimes referred to as *vocabularization*) means finding a suitable vocabulary V , but also learning how to use it, since any given string s of length $|s|$ has $2^{|s|-1}$ hypothetical segmentations, some of which containing segments that are not in the vocabulary.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The most important hyperparameter during vocabularization is the *vocabulary size* $|V|$ : when it is small, the learned vocabulary generally consists of characters and smaller strings, and words will be segmented into many tokens.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At larger sizes, it becomes affordable to dedicate tokens to full words, although depending on the preprocessor and tokenizer, it is not necessarily the case that large vocabularies will always use the largest token(s) available to segment a word.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Because tokens are not always full words, they may also be referred to as *subwords* and tokenization algorithms may be referred to as *subword tokenizers*.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is also to differentiate these systems from traditional terminology used in older information retrieval and natural language processing systems, where "tokenization" was used to denote what is today called "pretokenization" (very crudely: splitting into words).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In tokenizers that produce tokens that are *not* part of the vocabulary, a special token that does belong to the vocabulary is used as a generic stand-in, written as "[UNK]" for "unknown".
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In principle, any string could be hidden by such an [UNK].
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Indeed, in information retrieval, pretokenizers were themselves used as tokenizers (and also called "tokenizers") with a word-level vocabulary that contained an [UNK].
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Commonly used subword tokenization algorithms are byte pair encoding (BPE) and the unigram language model (ULM), which each include a vocabularization algorithm and a dedicated segmentation algorithm.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There also exist several segmentation algorithms that require no learning and can be applied given a vocabulary (produced by BPE or ULM, for example), like greedily recognising tokens in a pretoken by moving through it left-to-right.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Well-known software implementations of subword tokenizers are Hugging Face's `tokenizers` Python package implemented in Rust, and the `sentencepiece` Python package implemented in C++.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The latter package is named as such because one of its configuration options allows disabling the built-in pretokenizer, hence effectively making entire sentences a pretoken and thus having the tokenizer see entire sentences, rather than individual words.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each integer token identifier is converted into an embedding vector via a lookup table.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Equivalently stated, it multiplies a one-hot representation of the token identifier by an embedding matrix M .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The dimension of an embedding vector is called *hidden size* or *embedding size* and written as $d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This size is written as $d_{\text{model}}$ in the original transformer paper.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An un-embedding layer is almost the reverse of an embedding layer.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Whereas an embedding layer converts a token identifier into a vector, an un-embedding layer converts a vector into a probability distribution over tokens.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The un-embedding layer is a linear-softmax layer: $\mathrm {UnEmbed} (x)=\mathrm {softmax} (xW+b)$ The matrix has shape $(d_{\text{emb}},|V|)$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Some architectures use the transpose of the embedding matrix M as the un-embedding matrix W in order to avoid needing double the amount of embedding-related parameters and to avoid divergence during training.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A positional encoding is a fixed-size vector representation of the relative positions of tokens within a sequence: it provides the transformer model with information about *where* the words are in the input sequence.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This induces a bias towards the order of the input sequence, so that, for example, the input sequence "man bites dog" is processed differently from "dog bites man".
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The positional encoding is defined as a function of type $f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where d is a positive even integer.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Here, N is a free parameter that should be significantly larger than the biggest k that would be input into the positional encoding function.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The main reason for using this positional encoding function is that using it, shifts are linear transformations: $f(t+\Delta t)=\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t))f(t)$ where $\Delta t\in \mathbb {R}$ is the distance one wishes to shift.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position, and find the encoding of the position n-steps-ahead or n-steps-behind, by a matrix multiplication.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] By taking a linear sum, any convolution can also be implemented as linear transformations: $\sum _{j}c_{j}f(t+\Delta t_{j})=\left(\sum _{j}c_{j}\,\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t_{j}))\right)f(t)$ for any constants $c_{j}$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position and find a linear sum of the encoded locations of its neighbors.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This sum of encoded positions, when fed into the attention mechanism, would create attention weights on its neighbors, much like what happens in a convolutional neural network language model.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In typical implementations, all operations are done over the real numbers, not the complex numbers, but since complex multiplication can be implemented as real 2-by-2 matrix multiplication, this is a mere notational difference.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Like earlier seq2seq models, the original transformer model used an **encoder–decoder** architecture.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The encoder consists of encoding layers that process all the input tokens together one layer after another, while the decoder consists of decoding layers that iteratively process the encoder's output and the decoder's output tokens so far.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The purpose of each encoder layer is to create contextualized representations of the tokens, where each representation corresponds to a token that "mixes" information from other input tokens via self-attention mechanism.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Both the encoder and decoder layers have a feed-forward neural network for additional processing of their outputs and contain residual connections and layer normalization steps.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These feed-forward layers contain most of the parameters in a transformer model.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The feedforward network (FFN) modules in a transformer are 2-layered multilayer perceptrons: $\mathrm {FFN} (x)=\phi (xW^{(1)}+b^{(1)})W^{(2)}+b^{(2)}$ where $W^{(1)}$ and $W^{(2)}$ are weight matrices and $b^{(1)}$ and $b^{(2)}$ are bias vectors, and $\phi$ is its activation function.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The original transformer used ReLU activation.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The number of neurons in the middle layer is called *intermediate size* (GPT), *filter size* (BERT), or *feedforward size* (BERT).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is typically larger than the embedding size.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, in both GPT-2 series and BERT series, the intermediate size of a model is 4 times its embedding size: $d_{\text{ffn}}=4d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention mechanism used in the transformer architecture are scaled dot-product attention units.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For each unit, the transformer model learns three weight matrices: the query weights $W^{Q}$ , the key weights $W^{K}$ , and the value weights $W^{V}$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The module takes three sequences, a query sequence, a key sequence, and a value sequence.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The query sequence is a sequence of length $\ell _{\text{seq, query}}$ , and each entry is a vector of dimension $d_{\text{emb, query}}$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly for the key and value sequences.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For each vector $x_{i,{\text{query}}}$ in the query sequence, it is multiplied by a matrix $W^{Q}$ to produce a query vector $q_{i}=x_{i,{\text{query}}}W^{Q}$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The matrix of all query vectors is the query matrix: $Q=X_{\text{query}}W^{Q}$ Similarly, we construct the key matrix $K=X_{\text{key}}W^{K}$ and the value matrix $V=X_{\text{value}}W^{V}$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is usually the case that all $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ are square matrices, meaning $d_{\text{emb, query}}=d_{\text{query}}$ , etc.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Attention weights are calculated using the query and key vectors: the attention weight $a_{ij}$ from token i to token j is the dot product between $q_{i}$ and $k_{j}$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention weights are divided by the square root of the dimension of the key vectors, ${\sqrt {d_{k}}}$ , which stabilizes gradients during training, and passed through a softmax which normalizes the weights.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The fact that $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ are different matrices allows attention to be non-symmetric: if token i attends to token j (i.e. $q_{i}\cdot k_{j}$ is large), this does not necessarily mean that token j will attend to token i (i.e. $q_{j}\cdot k_{i}$ could be small).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output of the attention unit for token i is the weighted sum of the value vectors of all tokens, weighted by $a_{ij}$ , the attention from token i to each token.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention calculation for all tokens can be expressed as one large matrix calculation using the softmax function, which is useful for training due to computational matrix operation optimizations that quickly compute matrix operations.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The matrices Q , K and V are defined as the matrices where the i th rows are vectors $q_{i}$ , $k_{i}$ , and $v_{i}$ respectively.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] where the softmax is applied over each of the rows of the matrix.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The number of dimensions in a query vector is *query size* $d_{\text{query}}$ and similarly for the *key size* $d_{\text{key}}$ and *value size* $d_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output dimension of an attention head is its *head dimension* $d_{\text{head}}$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention mechanism requires the following three equalities to hold: $\ell _{\text{seq, key}}=\ell _{\text{seq, value}},\;d_{\text{query}}=d_{\text{key}},\;d_{\text{value}}=d_{\text{head}}$ but is otherwise unconstrained.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the attention head is used in a self-attention fashion, then $X_{\text{query}}=X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the attention head is used in a cross-attention fashion, then usually $X_{\text{query}}\neq X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is theoretically possible for all three to be different, but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One set of $\left(W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}\right)$ matrices is called an *attention head*, and each layer in a transformer model has multiple attention heads.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] While each attention head attends to the tokens that are relevant to each token, multiple attention heads allow the model to do this for different definitions of "relevance".
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, the query and key projection matrices, $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ , which are involved in the attention score computation, defines the "relevance".
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Meanwhile, the value projection matrix $W^{V}$ , in combination with the part of the output projection matrix $W^{O}$ , determines how the attended tokens influence what information is passed to subsequent layers and ultimately the output logits.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In addition, the scope of attention, or the range of token relationships captured by each attention head, can expand as tokens pass through successive layers.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the model to capture more complex and long-range dependencies in deeper layers.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Many transformer attention heads encode relevance relations that are meaningful to humans.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, some attention heads can attend mostly to the next word, while others mainly attend from verbs to their direct objects.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The computations for each attention head can be performed in parallel, which allows for fast processing.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The outputs for the attention layer are concatenated to pass into the feedforward neural network layers.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is theoretically possible for each attention head to have a different head dimension $d_{\text{head}}$ , but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As an example, in the smallest GPT-2 model, there are only self-attention mechanisms.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer architecture is constructed to calculate output tokens iteratively.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Assuming $t=0$ refers to the calculation of the first output token $i=0$ , for step $t>0$ , the output token $i=0$ shall remain constant.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This ensures properties of the model similar to autoregressive models.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Therefore, at every time step t , the calculation for all outputs i should not have access to tokens at position j for $j>=i$ (as it naturally is the case for time step $t=i$ , when tokens $j>t$ are not yet calculated).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In words, it means that each token can pay attention to itself, and every token before it, but not any after it.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A non-masked attention module can be thought of as a masked attention module where the mask has all entries zero.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As an example of an uncommon use of mask matrix, the XLNet considers all masks of the form $PM_{\text{causal}}P^{-1}$ , where P is a random permutation matrix.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An encoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple encoder layers.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each encoder layer consists of two major components: a self-attention mechanism and a feed-forward layer.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It takes an input as a sequence of input vectors, applies the self-attention mechanism, to produce an intermediate sequence of vectors, then applies the feed-forward layer for each vector individually.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] where ${\text{FFN}}$ stands for "feed-forward network".
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] We can more succinctly write it as ${\text{EncoderLayer}}(H)={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H))$ with the implicit convention that the ${\text{FFN}}$ is applied to each row of the matrix individually.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The first encoder layer takes the sequence of input vectors from the embedding layer, producing a sequence of vectors.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This sequence of vectors is processed by the second encoder, and so on.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output from the final encoder layer is then used by the decoder.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As the encoder processes the entire input all at once, every token can attend to every other token (all-to-all attention), so there is no need for causal masking.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A decoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple decoder layers, followed by an un-embedding layer.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each decoder consists of three major components: a causally masked self-attention mechanism, a cross-attention mechanism, and a feed-forward neural network.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The decoder functions in a similar fashion to the encoder, but an additional attention mechanism is inserted which instead draws relevant information from the encodings generated by the encoders.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This mechanism can also be called the *encoder–decoder attention*.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Like the first encoder, the first decoder takes positional information and embeddings of the output sequence as its input, rather than encodings.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer must not use the current or future output to predict an output, so the output sequence must be partially masked to prevent this reverse information flow.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows for autoregressive text generation.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For decoding, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because a token cannot attend to tokens not yet generated.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Thus, the self-attention module in the decoder is causally masked.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In contrast, the cross-attention mechanism attends to the output vectors of the encoder, which is computed before the decoder starts decoding.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Consequently, there is no need for masking in the cross-attention mechanism.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Schematically, we have: ${\begin{aligned}H'&={\text{MaskedMultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H)\\{\text{DecoderLayer}}(H)&={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H',H^{E},H^{E}))\end{aligned}}$ where $H^{E}$ is the matrix with rows being the output vectors from the encoder.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The last decoder is followed by a final un-embedding layer to produce the output probabilities over the vocabulary.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then, one of the tokens is sampled according to the probability, and the decoder can be run again to produce the next token, etc., autoregressively generating output text.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each encoder layer contains 2 sublayers: the self-attention and the feedforward network.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each decoder layer contains 3 sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, the cross-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The final points of detail are the residual connections and layer normalization, (denoted as "LayerNorm", or "LN" in the following), which while conceptually unnecessary, are necessary for numerical stability and convergence.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The residual connections are introduced to avoid vanishing gradient issues and stabilize the training process.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They can be expressed by $x\mapsto F(x)+x$ , where F is a given component of the transformer.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Adding the input x can preserve the input information and avoid issues when the gradient of $F(x)$ is close to zero.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly to how the feedforward network modules are applied individually to each vector, the LayerNorm is also applied individually to each vector.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There are two common conventions in use: the *post-LN* and the *pre-LN* convention.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the post-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (x))$ where $\mathrm {Sublayer} (x)$ is the function implemented by the sublayer itself.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the pre-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x))$ The original 2017 transformer used the post-LN convention.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It was difficult to train and required careful hyperparameter tuning and a "warm-up" in learning rate, where it starts small and gradually increases.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The pre-LN convention, proposed several times in 2018, was found to be easier to train, requiring no warm-up, leading to faster convergence.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer architecture, being modular, allows variations.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Several common variations are described here.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An "encoder-only" transformer applies the encoder to map an input text into a sequence of vectors that represent the input text.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is usually used for text embedding and representation learning for downstream applications.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are less often used currently, as they were found to be not significantly better than training an encoder–decoder transformer, then taking just the encoder.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are also referred to as "all-to-all" or "BERT-like".
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A "decoder-only" transformer is not literally decoder-only, since without an encoder, the cross-attention mechanism has nothing to attend to.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Thus, the decoder layers in a decoder-only transformer is composed of just two sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The models in the GPT series and Chinchilla series are decoder-only.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are also referred to as "autoregressive" or "causal".
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An "encoder–decoder" transformer is generally the same as the original transformer, with 2 sublayers per encoder layer and 3 sublayers per decoder layer, etc.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They might have minor architectural improvements, such as alternative activation functions, changing the location of normalization, etc.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is also usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The models in the T5 series are encoder–decoder.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A "prefixLM" (prefix language model) is a decoder-only architecture, but with prefix masking, which is different from causal masking.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, it has mask of the form $M_{\text{prefixLM}}={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {0} &-\infty \\\mathbf {0} &M_{\text{causal}}\end{bmatrix}}$ where the first columns correspond to the "prefix", and the subsequent columns correspond to the autoregressively generated text based on the prefix.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They resemble encoder–decoder models, but has less "sparsity".
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Such models are rarely used, though they are cited as theoretical possibilities and benchmarked comparisons.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, in 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model with a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model, as transformer-based decoders did not appear to significantly increase quality unlike the encoder, while the RNN decoder was much faster.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The original transformer uses ReLU activation function.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Other activation functions were developed.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The Llama series and PaLM used SwiGLU; both GPT-1 and BERT used GELU.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Alternative activation functions are often used in combination with Gated Linear Units in the feedforward module.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The normalization used in the transformer can be different from LayerNorm.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] One example is RMSNorm which is used in the Llama series.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Other examples include ScaleNorm and FixNorm.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Transformers may use other positional encoding methods than sinusoidal.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The original transformer paper reported using a learned positional encoding, but finding it not superior to the sinusoidal one.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Later, found that causal masking itself provides enough signal to a transformer decoder that it can learn to implicitly perform absolute positional encoding without the positional encoding module.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Then the RoPE encoding is applied to each pair of coordinates.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The benefit of RoPE is that the dot-product between two vectors depends on their relative location only: ${\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n{\big )}={\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m+k{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n+k{\big )}$ for any integer k .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] ALiBi (Attention with Linear Biases) is not a *replacement* for the positional encoder on the original transformer.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Instead, it is an *additional* positional encoder that is directly plugged into the attention mechanism.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The idea being that the linear bias matrix is a softened mask.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Just as 0 represent full attention paid, and $-\infty$ represents no attention paid, the linear bias matrix increases attention paid in one direction and decreases attention paid in the other direction.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] ALiBi allows pretraining on short context windows, then fine-tuning on longer context windows.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Since it is directly plugged into the attention mechanism, it can be combined with any positional encoder that is plugged into the "bottom" of the entire network (which is where the sinusoidal encoder on the original transformer, as well as RoPE and many others, are located).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Relative Position Encodings is similar to ALiBi, but more generic: ${\begin{aligned}{\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}\left({\frac {QK^{\mathrm {T} }}{\sqrt {d_{k}}}}+B\right)V\end{aligned}}$ where B is a Toeplitz matrix, that is, $B_{i,j}=B_{i',j'}$ whenever $i-j=i'-j'$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This is contrasted with the original sinusoidal positional encoding, which is an "absolute positional encoding".
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The transformer model has been implemented in standard deep learning frameworks such as TensorFlow and PyTorch.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] *Transformers* is a library produced by Hugging Face that supplies transformer-based architectures and pretrained models.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] When an autoregressive transformer is used for inference, such as generating text, the query vector is different at each step, but the already-computed key and value vectors are always the same.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The **KV caching** method saves the computed key and value vectors at each attention block, so that they are not recomputed at each new token.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] PagedAttention applies memory paging to KV caching.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If a transformer is used with a baked-in prompt, such as ["You are a customer support agent..."], then the key and value vectors can be computed for the prompt, and saved on disk.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The saving in compute is significant when the model is used for many short real-time interactions, such as in online chatbots.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In general, when a user uses an autoregressive transformer to generate a continuation to a sequence of tokens, the model would first perform a forward-pass on this sequence, whereby the KV caches over this sequence are computed.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Hyperscalers serving large Transformer models may use **disaggregated inference**, wherein prefilling and decoding are performed on separately specialized hardware.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] FlashAttention is an algorithm that implements the transformer attention mechanism efficiently on a GPU.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It is a communication-avoiding algorithm that performs matrix multiplications in blocks, such that each block fits within the cache of a GPU, and by careful management of the blocks it minimizes data copying between GPU caches (as data movement is slow).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The FlashAttention method is a communication-avoiding algorithm that fuses these operations into a single loop, increasing the arithmetic intensity.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In practice, FlashAttention operates over multiple queries and keys per loop iteration, in a similar way as blocked matrix multiplication.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If backpropagation is needed, then the output vectors and the intermediate arrays $[m_{1},\dots ,m_{N}],[\ell _{1},\dots ,\ell _{N}]$ are cached, and during the backward pass, attention matrices are rematerialized from these, making it a form of gradient checkpointing.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] An improved version, FlashAttention-2, was developed to cater to the rising demand for language models capable of handling longer context lengths.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It offers enhancements in work partitioning and parallelism, enabling it to achieve up to 230 TFLOPs/s on A100 GPUs (FP16/BF16), a 2x speed increase over the original FlashAttention.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Key advancements in FlashAttention-2 include the reduction of non-matmul FLOPs, improved parallelism over the sequence length dimension, better work partitioning between GPU warps, and added support for head dimensions up to 256 and multi-query attention (MQA) and grouped-query attention (GQA).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Benchmarks revealed FlashAttention-2 to be up to 2x faster than FlashAttention and up to 9x faster than a standard attention implementation in PyTorch.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Future developments include optimization for new hardware like H100 GPUs and new data types like FP8.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] FlashAttention-4 focuses on pipelining to increase instruction throughput, and was developed to perform particularly well on Blackwell GPUs.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multi-Query Attention changes the Multihead Attention mechanism.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This has a neutral effect on model quality and training speed, but increases inference speed.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] More generally, grouped-query attention (GQA) partitions attention heads into groups, each of which shares the key-value pair.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] MQA is GQA with one group, while standard Multihead Attention is GQA with the maximal number of groups.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multihead Latent Attention (MLA) is a low-rank approximation to standard MHA.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Specifically, each hidden vector, before entering the attention mechanism, is first projected to two low-dimensional spaces ("latent space"), one for query and one for key-value (KV vector).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This design minimizes the KV cache, as only the low-dimensional KV vector needs to be cached.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Speculative decoding is a method to accelerate token decoding.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Similarly to speculative execution in CPUs, future tokens are computed quickly, then verified.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If the quickly computed tokens are incorrect, they are discarded and computed slowly.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The key factor in speculative decoding is that a transformer decoder can verify faster than it can decode, in the following sense.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Suppose we have two transformer models like GPT-3 and GPT-3-small, both with a context window size of 512.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] To generate an entire context window autoregressively with greedy decoding with GPT-3, it must be run for 512 times, each time generating a token $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{512}$ , taking time $512T_{\text{GPT-3}}$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] However, if we had some educated guess for the values of these tokens, we could verify all of them in parallel, in one run of the model, by checking that each $x_{t}$ is indeed the token with the largest log-likelihood in the t -th output.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In speculative decoding, a smaller model or some other simple heuristic is used to generate a few speculative tokens that are subsequently verified by the larger model.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] These tokens are then run through the larger GPT-3 in one go.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Suppose that ${\tilde {x}}_{1}$ and ${\tilde {x}}_{2}$ are verified by GPT-3 as what it would have picked, then those are kept, but ${\tilde {x}}_{3}$ is not, so ${\tilde {x}}_{3},{\tilde {x}}_{4}$ are discarded, and GPT-3 is run on those.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For non-greedy decoding, similar ideas apply, except the speculative tokens are accepted or rejected stochastically, in a way that guarantees the final output distribution is the same as if speculative decoding was not used.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In Multi-Token Prediction, a single forward pass creates a final embedding vector, which then is un-embedded into a token probability.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] However, that vector can then be further processed by another transformer block to predict the *next* token, and so on for arbitrarily many steps into the future.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This trades off accuracy for speed, since each new token costs just one more transformer block, rather than the entire stack.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Training transformer-based architectures can be expensive, especially for long inputs.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Many methods have been developed to attempt to address the issue.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In the image domain, Swin transformer is an efficient architecture that performs attention inside shifting windows.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In the audio domain, SepTr decouples the attention in time and frequency domains.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] *Long Range Arena* (2020) is a standard benchmark for comparing the behavior of transformer architectures over long inputs.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The standard attention graph is either all-to-all or causal, both of which scales as $O(N^{2})$ where N is the number of tokens in a sequence.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Reformer (2020) reduces the computational load from $O(N^{2})$ to $O(N\ln N)$ by using locality-sensitive hashing and reversible layers.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Sparse attention uses attention graphs that grows slower than $O(N^{2})$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For example, BigBird (2020) uses random small-world networks which grows as $O(N)$ .
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Ordinary transformers require a memory size that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Attention-free transformers reduce this to a linear dependence while still retaining the advantages of a transformer by linking the key to the value.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Similarly for multiple queries, and for multihead attention.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This approximation can be computed in linear time, as we can compute the matrix $\varphi (k_{i})v_{i}^{T}$ first, then multiply it with the query.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Transformers can also be used/adapted for modalities (input or output) beyond just text, usually by finding a way to "tokenize" the modality.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multimodal models can either be trained from scratch, or by finetuning.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] A 2022 study found that transformers pretrained only on natural language can be finetuned on only 0.03% of parameters and become competitive with LSTMs on a variety of logical and visual tasks, demonstrating transfer learning.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The LLaVA was a vision-language model composed of a language model (Vicuna-13B) and a vision model (ViT-L/14), connected by a linear layer.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Vision transformers adapt the transformer to computer vision by breaking down input images as a series of patches, turning them into vectors, and treating them like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Conformer and later Whisper follow the same pattern for speech recognition, first turning the speech signal into a spectrogram, which is then treated like an image, i.e. broken down into a series of patches, turned into vectors and treated like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Perceivers are a variant of transformers designed for multimodality.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For image generation, notable architectures are DALL-E 1 (2021), Parti (2022), Phenaki (2023), and Muse (2023).
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Unlike later models, DALL-E is not a diffusion model.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Instead, it uses a decoder-only transformer that autoregressively generates a text, followed by the token representation of an image, which is then converted by a variational autoencoder to an image.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Parti is an encoder–decoder transformer, where the encoder processes a text prompt, and the decoder generates a token representation of an image.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Muse is an encoder-only transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] During generation, all input tokens are masked, and the highest-confidence predictions are included for the next iteration, until all tokens are predicted.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It is a bidirectional masked transformer conditioned on pre-computed text tokens.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The generated tokens are then decoded to a video.
[src:whisper-asr/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The transformer has had great success in natural language processing (NLP).
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] It is capable of transcribing speech in English and multiple other languages, and can translate several non-English languages into English.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Whisper is a weakly-supervised deep learning acoustic model, made using an encoder-decoder transformer architecture.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] OpenAI claims that the combination of different training data and post-training filtering used in its development has led to improved recognition of accents, background noise, and jargon compared to previous approaches.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] While the model does not outperform larger, more specialized models and still experiences AI hallucination, it has been showed to be useful for general sound recognition and has many applications across different industries.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Speech recognition has had a long history in research; the first approaches made use of statistical methods, such as dynamic time warping, and later hidden Markov models.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] At around the 2010s, deep neural network approaches became more common for speech recognition models, which were enabled by the availability of large datasets ("big data") and increased computational performance.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Transformers, introduced in 2017 by Google, displaced many prior state-of-the-art approaches across a wide range in machine learning, and started becoming the core neural architecture in fields such as language modeling and computer vision.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Weakly-supervised approaches to training acoustic models were recognized in the early 2020s as promising for speech recognition approaches using deep neural networks.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] According to a NYT report, in 2021 OpenAI believed they exhausted sources of higher-quality data to train their large language models and decided to complement scraped web text with transcriptions of YouTube videos and podcasts, and developed Whisper to solve this task.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Whisper Large V2 was released on December 8, 2022, followed by Whisper Large V3 being released in November 2023, during the OpenAI Dev Day.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] In March 2025, OpenAI released new transcription models based on GPT-4o and GPT-4o mini, both of which have lower error rates than Whisper.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The Whisper architecture is based on an encoder-decoder transformer.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Input audio is resampled to 16,000 Hertz (Hz) and converted to an 80-channel Log-magnitude Mel spectrogram using 25 ms windows with a 10 ms stride.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The spectrogram is then normalized to a [-1, 1] range with near-zero mean.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The encoder takes this Mel spectrogram as input and processes it.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] It first passes through two convolutional layers.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Sinusoidal positional embeddings are added.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] It is then processed by a series of Transformer encoder blocks (with pre-activation residual connections).
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The encoder's output is layer normalized.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The decoder is a standard transformer decoder.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] It has the same width and Transformer blocks as the encoder.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] It uses learned positional embeddings and tied input-output token representations (using the same weight matrix for both the input and output embeddings).
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] It uses a byte-pair encoding tokenizer, of the same kind as used in GPT-2.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] English-only models use the GPT-2 vocabulary, while multilingual models employ a re-trained multilingual vocabulary with the same number of words.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The training dataset consists of 680,000 hours of labeled audio-transcript pairs sourced from the internet using semi-supervised learning.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] This includes 117,000 hours in 96 non-English languages and 125,000 hours of X→English translation data, where X stands for any non-English language.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Speechless segments were also included to allow voice activity detection training.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] For the files still remaining after the filtering process, audio files were then broken into 30-second segments paired with the subset of the transcript that occurs within that time.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] If this predicted spoken language differed from the language of the text transcript associated with the audio, that audio-transcript pair was not used for training the speech recognition models, but instead for training translation.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The model was trained using the AdamW optimizer with gradient norm clipping and a linear learning rate decay with warmup, with batch size 256 segments.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Training proceeded for 1 million updates (approximately 2-3 epochs).
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] No data augmentation or regularization, except for the Large V2 model, which used SpecAugment, Stochastic Depth, and BPE Dropout.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The training used data parallelism with float16, dynamic loss scaling, and activation checkpointing.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] After training the first model, researchers ran it on different subsets of the training data, each representing a distinct source.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Data sources were ranked by a combination of their error rate and size.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Manual inspection of the top-ranked sources (high error, large size) helped determine if the source was low quality (e.g., partial transcriptions, inaccurate alignment).
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] After training, it was fine-tuned to suppress the prediction of speaker names and low-quality sources were then removed.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] While Whisper does not outperform models which specialize in the LibriSpeech dataset, when tested across many datasets, it is more robust and makes 55.2% fewer errors than other models.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Whisper has a differing error rate with respect to transcribing different languages, with a higher word error rate in languages not well-represented in the training data.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The authors found that multi-task learning improved overall performance compared to models specialized to one task.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] They conjectured that the best Whisper model trained is still underfitting the dataset, and larger models and longer training can result in better models.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Third-party evaluations have found varying levels of AI hallucination.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] A study of transcripts of public meetings found hallucinations in eight out of every 10 transcripts, while an engineer discovered hallucinations in "about half" of 100 hours of transcriptions and a developer identified them in "nearly every one" of 26,000 transcripts.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] A study of 13,140 short audio segments (averaging 10 seconds) found 187 hallucinations (1.4%), 38% of which generated text that could be harmful because it inserted false references to things like race, non-existent medications, or violent events that were not in the audio.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The model has been used as the base for many applications, such as a unified model for speech recognition and more general sound recognition.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Whisper has also been integrated into the workflow of biomedical research.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] In 2025, a study on Alzheimer's disease detection used the model to transcribe spontaneous speech recordings.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The transcripts that were generated by the model were combined with LLM vector embeddings and traditional classifiers to help classify the patients' health.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Another application is when OVALYTICS incorporated Whisper to transcribe YouTube videos and automate content moderation systems, which improved its detection of offensive content.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The model has also been used in academic libraries and cultral heritage institutions to generate transcripts and captions for their digitized audiovisual collections.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] In a 2025 case study, Emory University Libraries found that Whisper reduced the labor used in transcription by around 30-35%, shifting work from text creation to text correction.
[src:whisper-asr/whisper-speech-recognition-system] However, human review is still necessary to make sure accuracy, formatting, and accessibility are all standard.
